I see no reason to rename paste config file, because it's only used by api service, also the rename will break if you start api service without giving config file path."}, {'account_id': 4428, 'date': '2015-11-18 07:50:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi, Lei, I didn't find the problem you mentioned(using this patch, i don't need to specify --config-file), could you provide more info about this? thanks!"}, {'account_id': 16150, 'date': '2015-11-18 08:15:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

Hell Yingjun, I cloned this patch, manually set up virtual environment and searchlight according to the docs, when I tried to launch the api service by typing searchlight-api or searchlight-api --log-file etc/searchlight.conf, I got an error saying "ERROR: Unable to locate paste config file for searchlight-api".

I guess it's caused by the rename of searchlight-api-paste.ini file, from the code it seems that searchlight will use the command name as the prefix for the paste config file name if no config_file configuration is set.

Please correct if I got something wrong of the steps. Thanks'}, {'account_id': 4428, 'date': '2015-11-18 08:45:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thanks for the information, could you try to run `searchlight-api --config-file /etc/searchlight/searchlight.conf` to see if it work? btw, do you in IRC, we can talk there, my nickname is 'yingjun' in 'openstack-searchlight'."}, {'account_id': 16150, 'date': '2015-11-18 11:18:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

oops, seem to know what's wrong with the result. When I manually set up searchlight, I don't copy all the configuration files to '/etc/searchlight', which is a default configuration dir oslo config will search for. If I type 'searchlight-api --config-file /etc/searchlight/searchlight.conf', it works because if config file exists, it will replace suffix of config file to '-paste.ini' and use that name to search paste config. But in my environment simply typing 'searchlight-api' won't find any conf file, so it just uses another way to build paste file name, and that file doesn't exist, that's  why I get the error of unable to locate paste file.

The manual set up docs forget to mention copying config file to default dir thing.

Hope my understanding is right."}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2015-11-18 19:35:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I'm putting a -1 here for discussion. Based on discussion, we might decide this is okay as is.  But let's talk first.

I'm not excited about renaming the searchlight-api-paste.ini to just searchlight-paste.ini.  This feels like it backs us into a corner a bit.

I know why this is done and don't have a great solution off the top of my head without modifying searchlight/common code.

Basically, the code checks to see if there is a configuration file specified for the paste-ini[0] specifies a path to the paste file. This is something for deployers to set typically. Otherwise, it is looking for a file with the same starting name as the config_file option and appending -paste.ini to it [1].

 [0] https://github.com/openstack/searchlight/blob/master/searchlight/common/config.py#L132

 [1] https://github.com/openstack/searchlight/blob/master/searchlight/common/config.py#L115

We could require setting the paste deploy config file (like we do for config_file), but I'm not excited about that.  I'd rather not have to do that.

We could update the api launch command to send in conf_file[2] with the paste config file and resolve it similarly as [1] above. But then the logic in config to get this from a configuration option is bypassed [3]

 [2] https://github.com/openstack/searchlight/blob/master/searchlight/cmd/api.py#L87

 [3] https://github.com/openstack/searchlight/blob/master/searchlight/common/config.py#L159

Or we modify common/config to perhaps use the app_name to resolve the paste deploy config file when not specified, and then update [2] above to send in an app name of searchlight-api. This would also require updating the paste file itself to reflect the name change [3] [4].

 [3] https://github.com/openstack/searchlight/blob/master/etc/searchlight-api-paste.ini#L2
 [4] https://github.com/openstack/searchlight/blob/master/etc/searchlight-api-paste.ini#L5

Or just let this go in as is."}, {'account_id': 10063, 'date': '2015-11-18 23:47:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Looking around, most other services (glance being an exception) use <service>.conf and api-paste.ini. 

They do this with e.g.:

heat/common/config.py
31:    cfg.StrOpt('api_paste_config', default="api-paste.ini",

I suggest we use the same format. For reference, other services also have at their root 'etc/heat' or 'etc/nova'; glance is unusual in this respect also. I think that can be a later patch.'}, {'account_id': 4428, 'date': '2015-11-19 00:46:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Agree with Steve's suggestion, how about you? Travis."}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2015-11-19 02:13:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Rename default config

The default config file for searchlight is searchlight-api.conf despite
the fact it's used by the listener as well. It makes more sense to
rename the default to searchlight.conf.

Change-Id: I91744f02a27faa00f5ce082557cf78bf911fb085
Closes-bug: #1515015

subject: Add ipaddress to global-requirements.txt
revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-25 12:36:18.000000000', 'message': "Add ipaddress to global-requirements.txt

Port of the 3.3+ ipaddress module to 2.6, 2.7, 3.2

- Is the library actively maintained?

  Yes. See the recent commit history at:
  https://github.com/phihag/ipaddress/commits/master

- Is the library good code?

  Yes, given it's a port of a Python 3.3 module.

- Is the library python 3 compatible?

  Yes.

- Is the library license compatible?

  The license is Python Software Foundation License Version 2:
  https://github.com/phihag/ipaddress/blob/master/LICENSE

- Is the library already packaged in the distros we target (Ubuntu
  latest / Fedora latest)?

  Yes, it's packaged for Ubuntu, Fedora, CentOS.

- Is the function of this library already covered by other libraries
  in ``global-requirements.txt``?

  Not that I'm aware of.

Change-Id: Ic4ba8e767369a68f1ac9379dc71ec01b2967c6ce
"}]
commit_message:
Add ipaddress to global-requirements.txt

Port of the 3.3+ ipaddress module to 2.6, 2.7, 3.2

- Is the library actively maintained?

  Yes. See the recent commit history at:
  https://github.com/phihag/ipaddress/commits/master

- Is the library good code?

  Yes, given it's a port of a Python 3.3 module.

- Is the library python 3 compatible?

  Yes.

- Is the library license compatible?

  The license is Python Software Foundation License Version 2:
  https://github.com/phihag/ipaddress/blob/master/LICENSE

- Is the library already packaged in the distros we target (Ubuntu
  latest / Fedora latest)?

  Yes, it's packaged for Ubuntu, Fedora, CentOS.

- Is the function of this library already covered by other libraries
  in ``global-requirements.txt``?

  Not that I'm aware of.

Change-Id: Ic4ba8e767369a68f1ac9379dc71ec01b2967c6ce

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Don't build two tox envs for pep8(-constraints)

Currently, "tox -e pep8" builds two tox envs:
a "pep8" env, and then a "venv" env for genopts.

This is rather wasteful -- reuse the pep8 env
instead.

Change-Id: I8ba3d4e541f279e5bc62dba2b1caaac447fee7e3

commit_message:
Add check-requirements for cliff

cliff had made requirements check in
I40b2cf4030df66c851d7d11da4f81f645d110e76 and it was not enabled again.

Remove non-voting and make it voting in the gate as well - with using
the check-requirements template.

Note that cliff is in the global requirments sync, thus it should have a
gate job as explained in
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/requirements/#enforcement-in-projects

Change-Id: I4f22c58e469d42b64694123b13c64fe620bae1eb

commit_message:
Add "httpchk /versions" for glance-api haproxy.

With the default httpchk, glance-api always show warning in the logs
"WARNING glance.api.middleware.version_negotiation [..] Unknown version.
Returning version choices", with the /versions added, there is no
warning in the log.

Change-Id: I086cb23c30b9e3ddc5eac68cba42d03ed907138c
(cherry picked from commit 2a2da2f5aa271eebb06016060c62eee4618a0228)

commit_message:
[config-ref] Dummy include of conf-change tables

This patch includes most of the conf-changes tables in chapters to make
the build work without too much tweaks in conf.py.

Also manually fix a broken cinder table.

Change-Id: I9f77926bcd1f9688ae877951bd969ac5fcd29b61
Implements: blueprint config-ref-rst

commit_message:
Update juno for new dev work - 20 Nov 2015

Updates all repo SHAs to open up work on 10.1.18

The SHA's included in this patch are very likely to be the final SHA's
for Juno as the EOL for Juno in OpenStack is scheduled for today.

Closes-Bug: #1515001
Change-Id: Ieac6696abca78daa2b1fa377a680a86fff9a1d24

commit_message:
Add support of extend_kopts for ubuntu_bootstrap

This commit adds posibility to use different kernel boot options
if user would like to modify it. The extend_kopts.rb takes two strings,
compares them and modifies default kopts.

Implements: Blueprint modify-fuel-library
Change-Id: Iac69c8457bd0ce76a1082c98d679ff44f468bf1f

commit_message:
Modifying docimpact group

Modfying the default docimpact group for all projects (except Nova, Swift,
Glance, Keystone, and Cinder) to raise bugs in their own projects, rather
than openstack-manuals.

Change-Id: Ide50b2fcbb070943d2b7efed728c40383a05aed9
Implements-blueprint: review-docimpact

[zmq] Use PortOpt config option for ports

options (rpc_zmq_min_port, rpc_zmq_max_port) and other
port-related options.

commit_message:
[docs] Update error message

Error message changed when Update environment returns HTTP 400
at commit ac2b523302604abca83212233d5d68ea43651877.

before: Environment name must contain only alphanumeric or "_-."
        characters, must start with alpha
after : Environment name must contain at least one non-white
        space symbol

This patch fixes it in the doc.

Change-Id: I9bba2cb92cf8d034c54a6209a8ba60b3075b15db
Closes-Bug: #1519217

commit_message:
cells: skip 5 networking scenario tests that use floating IPs

These scenario tests run with neutron and rely on assigning floating IPs
which cells v1 doesn't support, so skip them.

Longer term I think we'll have a feature toggle in Tempest to allow
disabling these tests via config but this is quicker and easier for now
to get a cells v1 + neutron job in the experimental queue.

Change-Id: Ieb3b117449f56810f1a41fcf43e737ae919b8945

commit_message:
Bug fix while editing actions with missing keys

If a key is not present in the database, the panel failed to open the modal
windows for edition, this fix that by using the dict.get()

cherry-picked from: b08558eba43dfc45335ad817de327048ad76cf64

Change-Id: Ic5f5e216828f10d41f288408fc5109dc004c6ab9

commit_message:
Freezer Scheduler for Windows

Freezer now has support for scheduling jobs through windows service.

This windows service needs to be installed in user land rather than
service land, instructions are included in the README.rst

--no-api mode is not available on windows

Change-Id: I34db28ffc928703b01e6430a661214d66d81c518

commit_message:
Disable mistral-python34 in all branches except mitaka and higher

Support of python34 was implemented only in mitaka, so it was
incorrect to make this gate voting in all branches because now
merge patches in old stable branches is blocked.

Change-Id: I8772b59bd3b318f3c1caec6cc8a27a33af6bbf87

commit_message:
Add guidelines for release notes to devref

Starting from this cycle (and stable Liberty) we're using reno for
release notes. This commit adds guidelines on when a release note is
required to be added.

Change-Id: If5aa6ab8317ec2f4295d899a45f80f11504d2a2c

commit_message:
Change cluster to cluster_id in nodegroup

Introduced by change-id: I413f77ce1dca59ae2c48ba743513ddf5584713e8
Nodegroup 'cluster' field has been changed to 'cluster_id' in
nailgun. So we need to adjust fuelclient accordingly.

Also includes some changes in nodegroups unit tests.

Change-Id: Iba3df02142279c14910578770187ac93157190c4
Closes-bug: #1518341

Add BOOTIF=${mac} to the inspector iPXE template

It is required to determine the booting NIC.

commit_message:
Implement Gnocchi Statsd support

* Manage Gnocchi statsd package & service
* Manage Gnocchi configuration
* Complete example manifests and acceptance tests with the new class.
* Make sure db_sync is run before gnocchi services, otherwise statsd
  would fail to start.

Change-Id: Ib894571889a69e67760402217f9fc18a339ced19

Yeah, I wasn't sure why HIDDEN was implemented that way.  I've added Peter Razumovsky and Sergey Kraynev so they can weigh in."}, {'account_id': 6577, 'date': '2015-11-13 12:22:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Jason: tank you for adding me on review. 
I definitely against of using one more support status.
As I remember during implementation of HIDDEN status we discussed case when some operations will be prohibited for user.
However there was decision: do not do it, because it makes break backward compatibility:
 - for delete and update it's obvious
 - for create - I think it can partially affect user, e.g. during UpdateReplace

I hope, that I did not mixed it with some other discussion in the past :) Will add Steve. He can remember, what I said above."}, {'account_id': 7253, 'date': '2015-11-13 17:57:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi Sergey,

Can you elaborate on how it breaks backward compatibility?

If we could modify HIDDEN so that updates, deletes, and UpdateReplace creates are allowed, but new creates are not allowed, would that be acceptable?

Or if you think of some other way to solve this use case, please let me know.

Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 6577, 'date': '2015-11-17 14:26:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Jason: I personally agree with your suggestion about prohibiting new creates. However as I understand it will affects UpdateReplace mechanism or is it possible to find differences between new creates and creates during UpdateReplace? 

if it's possible, I don't mind ;) 
p.s. I hope, that I did not miss any special case which also may affect backward compatibility."}, {'account_id': 7253, 'date': '2015-11-17 21:49:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Add display_name to Quobyte backend volume name

Improves readability in Quobyte volume names by
using display_name and id to build the backend volume name.
The share display name is preserved to keep volume names easily
identifyable in the backend.
Adding the share id ensures uniqueness of
Quobyte backend volume names.

Implements: blueprint display-name-in-quobyte-backend

Change-Id: Ie7ffd3d45aa258bde3845547055ff3e85fffb8db

commit_message:
Add test with removing multirack cluster

* Remove deployed environment
* Check that nodes from custom nodegroup have 'ERROR' status after discovering
* Reset slaves from custom nodegroup and make sure they aren't discovered again

Change-Id: I9ae3a81a0125cfed9c8f9b9cfd971ebbec640428
Implements: blueprint test-custom-nodegroup-controllers

I think it makes a lot of sense to split this out into its own DevStack plugin.  It seems lots of things are moving that way and that's great.

I think it's worth noting that in this particular case, the code is used in voting gate jobs for nova, glance, and cinder.  Maybe it should be in openstack/ instead of stackforge/ ?  It could be another git repo under the DevStack project team.  I'd love to hear what Dean Troyer and other DevStack team members think."}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-06-10 13:23:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: -Code-Review

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-16 16:17:19.000000000', 'message': "Move Calico's mechanism driver to networking-calico

The Calico mechanism driver was previously part of
https://github.com/projectcalico/calico, but logically belongs in
networking-calico - the OpenStack/Neutron integration code for Calico
- and so is now moving to this repository.  As well as the mechanism
driver code, this move includes:

- unit testing for the mechanism driver

- creation of a neutron.ml2.mechanism_drivers entry point for the name
  'calico'

- requirements updates as needed for the new code.

Also, so that Calico's Debian and RPM package-based installations
continue to work, and so that existing installations can be smoothly
upgraded, this change adds Debian and RPM packaging to
networking-calico.  Established Calico installation instructions [1,2]
use the umbrella package names 'calico-control' and 'calico-compute'
to indicate whatever is needed to add Calico function to an OpenStack
controller and compute node respectively, and (as these are
OpenStack-specific concepts) responsibility for generating these
umbrella packages also now moves from
https://github.com/projectcalico/calico to networking-calico.

calico-control and calico-compute both depend on a third package,
'networking-calico', which is the package that contains
networking-calico's Python code.  Thus an install of the
'networking-calico' Debian or RPM package should be very similar to a
'pip install networking-calico' from PyPI.

[1] http://docs.projectcalico.org/en/latest/ubuntu-opens-install.html
[2] http://docs.projectcalico.org/en/latest/redhat-opens-install.html

Change-Id: I54724a4e4fbb465daddcff07e6da19cb91b2dc4a

commit_message:
Move Calico's mechanism driver to networking-calico

The Calico mechanism driver was previously part of
https://github.com/projectcalico/calico, but logically belongs in
networking-calico - the OpenStack/Neutron integration code for Calico
- and so is now moving to this repository.  As well as the mechanism
driver code, this move includes:

- unit testing for the mechanism driver

- creation of a neutron.ml2.mechanism_drivers entry point for the name
  'calico'

- requirements updates as needed for the new code.

Also, so that Calico's Debian and RPM package-based installations
continue to work, and so that existing installations can be smoothly
upgraded, this change adds Debian and RPM packaging to
networking-calico.  Established Calico installation instructions [1,2]
use the umbrella package names 'calico-control' and 'calico-compute'
to indicate whatever is needed to add Calico function to an OpenStack
controller and compute node respectively, and (as these are
OpenStack-specific concepts) responsibility for generating these
umbrella packages also now moves from
https://github.com/projectcalico/calico to networking-calico.

calico-control and calico-compute both depend on a third package,
'networking-calico', which is the package that contains
networking-calico's Python code.  Thus an install of the
'networking-calico' Debian or RPM package should be very similar to a
'pip install networking-calico' from PyPI.

[1] http://docs.projectcalico.org/en/latest/ubuntu-opens-install.html
[2] http://docs.projectcalico.org/en/latest/redhat-opens-install.html

Change-Id: I54724a4e4fbb465daddcff07e6da19cb91b2dc4a

commit_message:
Freescale ML2 driver code complete decomposition.

This removes all the artifacts specific to Freescale ML2 driver code
from the Neutron tree. The code is maintained at github repository.

Change-Id: I194a4da49058724766b7fde7343f85d19a75fe8c

[{'created': '2015-11-24 08:06:58.000000000', 'message': "Fix two errors in setup_training_guides

setup_training_guides was written assuming that the project would be
passed as the first argument, but it wasn't called like that. Change
the function to match others to hardcode the project, and look for the
version as the first argument.

Correct the path to the locale directory so that the Zanata client can
read and write translation files correctly.

Change-Id: Iacfd2e831d18af5870fc70a2a54e569d0924474e
"}]
commit_message:
Fix two errors in setup_training_guides

setup_training_guides was written assuming that the project would be
passed as the first argument, but it wasn't called like that. Change
the function to match others to hardcode the project, and look for the
version as the first argument.

Correct the path to the locale directory so that the Zanata client can
read and write translation files correctly.

Change-Id: Iacfd2e831d18af5870fc70a2a54e569d0924474e

commit_message:
Skip cinder tests if cinder is not available

Currently, cinder tests run even when the cinder service is not
available and fails. This commit skips the tests if the cinder
service is not available.

This patch also updates readme on using tox to run tempest tests.

Change-Id: Idd607012346004b39c9d4cbe752b0cdcfe3e3311

commit_message:
New operation env-template-create-env

After create a new template you need to create the environment from template.
You need a operation for this action. This is the new operation.

Implements blueprint: template-create-environment

Change-Id: If9d8df008a167a371af38d758ecf356e14b8510d

commit_message:
Add related parameters to designate::central

This patch is aim to add the following params in to designate::central
  - workers
  - threads
  - max_domain_name_len
  - max_recordset_name_len
  - min_ttl
  - default_pool_id

Change-Id: I00a9bb85675983d0ba0f58ef0fa58fd504b11095
closes-Bug: #1482004

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

[{'created': '2015-11-12 08:00:42.000000000', 'message': 'Storwize: Implement v2 replication (unmanaged)

Storwize supports two major types for volume replications:
split IO and sync (global mirror and metro mirror).

This patch is dedicated to implement the replication for
the mode of splitio (stretched cluster) in the unmanaged
Storwize back-ends. For this mode, volume is replicable when
the replication target is on the same SVC storage as the
replication source. Multiple configuration for replication_device
is not applicable. The option replication_device can
only be set with a single dict for splitio (stretched cluster).
The replication_mode in replication_device must be set to
splitio.

The volume type needs to associate with the extra spec
with 'replication_enabled' equaling to "<is> True", and
'replication_type' equaling to 'splitio'.

The replication can be configured via either multi-backend
on one host, or on seperate hosts.

Options to be put in cinder.conf, where the primary back-end
is located:

[sv1]
san_login = admin
san_password = admin
san_ip = 192.168.0.11
volume_driver = cinder.volume.drivers.ibm.storwize_svc.\
                StorwizeSVCDriver
volume_backend_name = sv1
storwize_svc_volpool_name=cinder
replication_device = replication_mode:splitio,
                     remote_device_id:svc_id_target,
                     san_ip:192.168.0.11,san_login:admin,
                     san_password:admin,pool_name=cinder_target

Partial-implements: blueprint ibm-storwize-v2-replication
DocImpact

Change-Id: Ib07712c6c878d54314555456991eaa335855ab14

commit_message:
refine the ironic installation guide

From the Juno version, we have the OpenStackClient to identify
the component. So we can substitute OpenStackClient for keystone
to identify the ironic.
I checked the OpenStackClient commands guide:
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/OpenStackClient/Commands#endpoint
The OpenStackClient API version is:API v2.0
The OpenStackClient command is:
os endpoint create
    --publicurl <public-url>
    [--adminurl <admin-url>]
    [--internalurl <internal-url>]
    [--region <endpoint-region>]
    <service>
And the keystone command is:
keystone endpoint-create
    [--region <endpoint-region>]
    [--service_id <service-id>]
    [--publicurl <public-url>]
    [--adminurl <admin-url>]
    [--internalurl <internal-url>]
Change-Id: I51ced0aeb04aed486cbe644305a9c19233e1d398

Miles, that is exactly what I'm thinking.  We will surely have some operators that will want to lock their environments to only permit TLS 1.2 or 1.3 (Once it is out of draft).  Possibly even what encryption algorithms they want to permit to be utilized in their environment, although at the same time that is ultimately a deficiency in the oslo library's capabilities.  But a specification would, in my mind have helped flush that detail out as a work-item to help drive things forward.

In-line, I've suggested basis for configuration parameter description text and a noted a nit regarding method doc string. '}, {'created': '2015-11-23 01:24:22.000000000', 'message': "Use paramiko transport for gate check jobs

There have been a lot of random ssh connection errors in the gate jobs lately
where the ssh connection itself is successful, but then no data can be sent
over the open connection. Ansible usually throws an error like this:

    SSH Error: data could not be sent to the remote host. Make sure this host
    can be reached over ssh

After digging in Ansible's code, this occurs when the ssh connection is open,
but no data can be written to the ssh connection. Ansible developers are
switching the default transport to paramiko for some modern operating systems
(like OS X El Capitan) due to some reliability issues with the ssh client.

commit_message:
Use paramiko transport for gate check jobs

There have been a lot of random ssh connection errors in the gate jobs lately
where the ssh connection itself is successful, but then no data can be sent
over the open connection. Ansible usually throws an error like this:

    SSH Error: data could not be sent to the remote host. Make sure this host
    can be reached over ssh

After digging in Ansible's code, this occurs when the ssh connection is open,
but no data can be written to the ssh connection. Ansible developers are
switching the default transport to paramiko for some modern operating systems
(like OS X El Capitan) due to some reliability issues with the ssh client.

Change-Id: Ia2e76a12e8b06dce448ed7e122b60386f5856d50

commit_message:
Disable ssh pipelining for gate check jobs

There have been a lot of random ssh connection errors in the gate jobs lately
where the ssh connection itself is successful, but then no data can be sent
over the open connection. Ansible usually throws an error like this:

    SSH Error: data could not be sent to the remote host. Make sure this host
    can be reached over ssh

After digging in Ansible's code, this occurs when the ssh connection is open,
but no data can be written to the ssh connection.

In order to work around this issue until Ansible 2 is released, SSH Pipelining
is being disabled.

Change-Id: Id68b3dd22cc3c57ab49822635bb9bee2370f0aef

commit_message:
Convert gate to Ansible setup

To support multinode we must now distribute our setup to multiple
hosts. Instead of making special rules for this, we are going to
convert our existing setup to Ansible. This way both setup proceedures
take place in the exact same fashion.

Partially-Implements: blueprint multinode-gate
Change-Id: I43ece298bba994e9b5083403ef3cf6d4245cda6d
(cherry picked from commit f9ee96f21695f7eba81c07e257eda3a080108b70)

Add negative test for cfapi last_status route.

- Add test which will check, that cfapi returns expected error-code
from last_status request, if requested instance_id doesn't exist.

Change-Id: I2845aad6d08182f64dd4b6ce5f494c564c989c63
Targets: blueprint murano-cfapi-func-tests

commit_message:
[cfapi] Prevent code 500 if instance, environment or service doesn't exists.

- Return 410 code if service/environment/instance_id doesn't exists
 as mentioned in cfapi service broker guide
(https://docs.cloudfoundry.org/services/api.html#asynchronous-operations)

Change-Id: I07bfaf8465649c77d06b881b24c49bce3d8d75ed
Closes-Bug: #1516749

commit_message:
Add provision and deprovision test for cfapi

- Add Mock app which will be imported during the test run.
This app will be deployed through Cloudfoundry API Murano Service
Broker.
- Change plugin to make possible create a zip archive
in murano_tempest_tests directory.
- Add application_catalog client into services directory to
perform operations with packages.
- Add utils to make possible dummy app generation.
- Add functions to provide additional functionality to
service_broker client.
- Add functions to service_broker base to make cleanups easier.
- Add provision and deprovision test.

Targets: blueprint murano-cfapi-func-tests

Change-Id: I6fc75f53b8f0c7b2a96ff2e1d5a63529efaf98df

commit_message:
Use appropriate types to store IP and MAC addrs

In PostgreSQL there are special types for storing IPv4, IPv6 address and
subnetworks and also MAC addresses. Storing data in these types is more
efficient than in strings because it requires less space. In addition,
it provides additional operations for columns of these types.

This patch changes types of some columns for models such as:

    IPAddr
        ip_addr: inet

    IPAddrRange
        first: inet
        last: inet

    Node
        mac: macaddr
        ip: inet

    NodeNICInterface
        mac: macaddr
        ip_addr: inet
        netmask: inet

    NodeNICInterface
        mac: macaddr

    NetworkGroup
        cidr: cidr
        gateway: inet

    NeutronConfig
        base_mac: macaddr
        internal_cidr: cidr
        internal_gateway: inet
        baremetal_gateway: inet

    NovaNetworkConfig
        fixed_networks_cidr: cidr

Co-Authored-By: Ilya Kharin <ikharin@mirantis.com>
Change-Id: Id8431eb7d2e3ca1a1cc29fc865d57359b29d0e35
Partial-Bug: #1484973

commit_message:
remove config files when run clean.sh

Currently we don't remove Ceilometer config files when ./clean.sh
is run, which should be fixed because it will bite developers when
they test change related to devstack script.

Note, this patch also removes ceilometer api log files when WSGI
is not enabled.

Change-Id: I3fd62787708cf64d1860b2b64d25773e79b17fe9
Closes-Bug: #1509253

commit_message:
Set DNS nameserver while configuring tenant network

Follow the install-guide more closely by setting the DNS nameserver
in config_tenant_network.

Use the same DNS nameserver (8.8.4.4) as the install-guide.

Don't set dnsmasq_dns_servers in setup_neutron_network anymore.

Change-Id: I626243f0e3f236f064e84921d3ffdcf0eba3aaeb

commit_message:
Rename "endpoint" to "credential" (part 1)

Copied rally/common/objects/endpoint.py to credential.py
Marked objects.Endpoint as deprecated
Modified use of objects.Endpoint to objects.Credential
Variable and key names are not changed in this patch

Partial-Bug: #1447682
Change-Id: Ia62881473d1bf63f952528b66e7420eea6323f08

commit_message:
Enable Fernet token support

  - use fernet token by default
  - generate and install keys for fernet
  - add noop tests for new parameters

Co-Authored-By: Vasyl Saienko <vsaienko@mirantis.com>

Implements blueprint: fernet-tokens-support

Failed test:
master.fuel-library.pkgs.ubuntu.neutron_vlan_ha

This test contains this error: "Failed to execute hook 'copy_files' File does
not exist or is not readable /var/lib/fuel/keys/1/fernet-keys/1".
The cause of the issue is that only puppet manifest of Fuel Master node is
updated, but puppet manifests in docker container are not changed.

Change-Id: I98c677f1418e130c304c96eacc75e94f0180788a

Closes-Bug: #1519244

commit_message:
Correct docstring warnings

There were warnings printed when docs were generated:

 docstring of keystone.assignment.core.Manager.create_grant:8:
 ERROR: Unexpected indentation.

These are because the docstrings were not valid rst. The docstrings
are corrected.

In the case of create_grant, the problem is that the docstring of
the wrapper was used, so @functools.wraps is added so that the
docstring of the function is used rather than the wrapper. Also,
the wrapper's docstring was incorrectly formatted.

Also, corrected other issues with docstrings.

Change-Id: Ide6a85365f71330bf4caa24babc3bfe56174fc0f

commit_message:
Remove vendor/downstream specific code

Also fix broken dependency of Package['pacemaker']
onto undef File, which was present in the code but
did nothing in fact (A-> undef -> B -> C == B -> C)

TODO figure out what to do with
./deployment/puppet/nailgun/files/Release-auxiliary

Change-Id: Ic8f495871ee4a1a9e7889c2b487cfd8d8b560139
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

[{'created': '2015-11-24 14:37:53.000000000', 'message': "Don't trigger gate-fuel-web-python26 job for fuel-web

gate-fuel-web-python26 job uses PostgreSQL version without
JSON DB type support, which is required for fuel-web. There's no
sense in keeping this job even in non-voting mode because it will
always fail.

Change-Id: Ide7b77777ca5334748f367c4c6bd244fd052c979
Closes-Bug: #1519371
"}]
commit_message:
Don't trigger gate-fuel-web-python26 job for fuel-web

gate-fuel-web-python26 job uses PostgreSQL version without
JSON DB type support, which is required for fuel-web. There's no
sense in keeping this job even in non-voting mode because it will
always fail.

Change-Id: Ide7b77777ca5334748f367c4c6bd244fd052c979
Closes-Bug: #1519371

commit_message:
Switch CinderEnableIscsiBackend to CinderEnableLvmBackend

As pointed out in [1] and [2], referring to the Cinder LVM backend
with the iSCSI name might be confusing. This change changes the
template parameter to use the name LVM instead.

1. https://review.gerrithub.io/#/c/233751/
2. https://review.gerrithub.io/#/c/234597/

Change-Id: I17a6236a435c764b3934db511dadd81cf1d26425

commit_message:
Fix job deffinition for ceph job

Recently, I4f70a3785ea4aeb38c3ebd8fd6a74ed3d035fa1a landed and fixed the
definition for the ceph-src job. This fix copies the same fix from that
job into the non-src ceph job as it's been failing in stable branches
with the same footprint.

The change removes the TEMPEST_FULL definition as the original fix did
and it changes the regular expression to align both jobs.

Change-Id: If289bfe3a5e4958411c8fae41a73971433c00d8b

commit_message:
midonet-db-manage: Retire migration functionalities

Remove sub-commands inherited from neutron-db-manage.
"neutron-db-manage --subproject networking-midonet" should be
used instead.

This commit doesn't remove the command itself as it has some
midonet specific sub-commands.  (task-list etc)

Closes-Bug: #1518180
Change-Id: I6ceb2f05190ee458943aa5c0748b02a0fca333be

commit_message:
Refactor IRMCVirtualMediaIscsiDeploy by applying new BootInterface

This patch refactors IRMCVirtualMediaIscsiDeploy by applying new
BootInterface. Consequently IRMCVirtualMediaIscsiDeploy is divided
into IRMCVirtualMediaBoot and IRMCVirtualMediaIscsiDeploy.

Implements: blueprint irmc-driver-uses-boot-interface

Change-Id: I709f3eb9b7798fa9b8a415bafbebbc24b03c5ebe

commit_message:
Remove python26 from keystone projects

Signal that we won't be worring about py26 compatability
anymore from now on, by removing the gate jobs for
keystone projects.

Change-Id: If30ab3c96d99ef118d0d970b57b21032d4e9050d
Closes-Bug: #1519449

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-23 18:22:26.000000000', 'message': 'Use wait_is_ready for finial choice

The old choice is wait_for_status, but using wait_is_ready could move
deletion logic and status check to new callbacks. And the callbacks'
arguments will not bother the wait_is_ready functions. The arguments for
wait_is_ready is only related wait logic, some example codes:

[task/utils.py]
def resource_deletion(resource):
    update = get_from_manager(resource)
    try:
        update(resource)
    except exceptions.GetResourceNotFound:
        return True
    return False

def resource_status(ready_status=[], failure_status=[]):
    """
    codes like wait_for_status, but it is a factury which produce
    callback here.
    """
    def callback(res):
        ...
    return callback

def wait_is_ready(resource, is_ready, timeout=60, interval=1):
    pass

[some scenario]

def xx_delete(self, xx):
    xx.delete()
    utils.wait_is_ready(xx, is_ready=utils.resource_deletion)

def xx_update(self, xx)
    xx.update(...)
    utils.wait_is_ready(xx, is_ready=utils.resource_status(
                ready_status=[],
                failure_status=[]))

Change-Id: Ie8f92b5fa4a24455dae4ed06447c7f3fb68fd387
'}, {'created': '2015-11-23 18:25:30.000000000', 'message': 'Use wait_is_ready for finial choice

The old choice is wait_for_status, but using wait_is_ready could move
deletion logic and status check to new callbacks. And the callbacks'
arguments will not bother the wait_is_ready functions. The arguments for
wait_is_ready is only related wait logic, some example codes:

[task/utils.py]
def resource_deletion(resource):
    update = get_from_manager(resource)
    try:
        update(resource)
    except exceptions.GetResourceNotFound:
        return True
    return False

def resource_status(ready_status=[], failure_status=[]):
    """
    codes like wait_for_status, but it is a factury which produce
    callback here.
    """
    def callback(res):
        ...
    return callback

def wait_is_ready(resource, is_ready, timeout=60, interval=1):
    pass

[some scenario]
def xx_delete(self, xx):
    xx.delete()
    utils.wait_is_ready(xx, is_ready=utils.resource_deletion)

def xx_update(self, xx)
    xx.update(...)
    utils.wait_is_ready(xx, is_ready=utils.resource_status(
                ready_status=["READY"],
                failure_status=["FAIL"]))

So, the wait_is_ready is clean and xx_delete and xx_update is still
readable.

commit_message:
Use wait_is_ready for finial choice

The old choice is wait_for_status, but using wait_is_ready could move
deletion logic and status check to new callbacks. And the callbacks'
arguments will not bother the wait_is_ready functions. The arguments for
wait_is_ready is only related wait logic, some example codes:

[task/utils.py]
def resource_deletion(resource):
    update = get_from_manager(resource)
    try:
        update(resource)
    except exceptions.GetResourceNotFound:
        return True
    return False

def resource_status(ready_status=[], failure_status=[]):
    """
    codes like wait_for_status, but it is a factury which produce
    callback here.
    """
    def callback(res):
        ...
    return callback

def wait_is_ready(resource, is_ready, timeout=60, interval=1):
    pass

[some scenario]
def xx_delete(self, xx):
    xx.delete()
    utils.wait_is_ready(xx, is_ready=utils.resource_deletion)

def xx_update(self, xx)
    xx.update(...)
    utils.wait_is_ready(xx, is_ready=utils.resource_status(
                ready_status=["READY"],
                failure_status=["FAIL"]))

So, the wait_is_ready is clean and xx_delete and xx_update is still
readable.

Change-Id: Ie8f92b5fa4a24455dae4ed06447c7f3fb68fd387

commit_message:
Remove iso8601 dependency

Mistral does not import and use this module directly, no need to list
it in the requirements and no need to set debug level for this module.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I42d5661dce0d23777fc5801c20a3a7c86756007d

commit_message:
Removing wait() when initializing notification listener

According to [1],the correct usage is to call stop() before wait(), so in
mistral case, we should never call stop() and wait() in initialization of
engine and executor service.

[1]:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.messaging/notification_listener.html

Change-Id: Ic6a802bff35a6a6fdfadf38474782efd12fd34d8
Closes-Bug: #1514459

commit_message:
Fix state change on exception during task state change

If there is an exception during on_task_state_change, particularly if
there is a YAQL evaluation error in the input of the next task, the state
of the current task and related action execution will be marked ERROR for
sync task and rolled back for async task, leaving the task as orphaned in
RUNNING state in most cases. This is a workflow handling error and the
workflow execution state is already marked ERROR. The state of the current
task execution should not be affected.

Change-Id: Id28b0661c09efa80a666d9eb7606fb435641a989

commit_message:
Fixing SSH actions to use names of private keys

 * SSH action uses private key names instead of
   private keys themself. All private keys now
   should be in <user-home>/.ssh/, e.g. searching
   of key 'my_key.pem' will be at <user-home>/.ssh/my_key.pem
 * Fixed functional tests
 * Remove sudo while running tests

Closes-Bug: #1507600

Depends-On: Idc4340cda80d02f4ee88c91600b72d0f914c4084

Change-Id: I503d78ff541183ce850476229842fa6f20061a00

commit_message:
Add flavor argument to loadbalancer v2 create

Builds on cli changes for Neutron flavor framework, which have
now been merged.

The '--flavor' argument takes a flavor name or id, looking up the
id from name if needed.

The loadbalancer v2 service can be configured to use the flavor to
find the operator-selected provider and populate the provider field,
enabling dynamic operator control of which provider is being used on
creation.

Change-Id: I02ed05d56fab4d0f60a8616978970336b4415f2c
Implements: blueprint neutron-flavor-framework

While adding new security group rule 'Custom ICMP rule' when wrong ICMP 'type' or 'code' was given the errors it would show was 'Not a valid port number'; which is wrong or misleading. Before this patch, for checking/validating ICMP 'type' and 'code', the code for validating 'TCP ports' was used. Now that new improved code is available in 'oslo.utils.netutils' that does validation of ICMP 'type' and ICMP 'code' this code has been used in this patch.

Change-Id: I3c9debc0eb156a4a3932b5e3f4dd601a313d065e
Closes-Bug: #1511748

'Not a valid port number'; which is wrong or misleading. Before

code for validating 'TCP ports' was used. Now that new improved
code is available in 'oslo.utils.netutils' that does validation
of ICMP 'type' and ICMP 'code' this code has been used in this patch.

Change-Id: I3c9debc0eb156a4a3932b5e3f4dd601a313d065e
Closes-Bug: #1511748
"}, {'created': '2015-11-25 06:15:24.000000000', 'message': "ICMP type & code validation while adding Security Group rules

While adding new 'Security Group Rule' viz. 'Custom ICMP rule' when
wrong ICMP 'type' or 'code' was given the errors it would show were
'Not a valid port number'; which is misleading. The errors should
rather be 'Not a valid ICMP type' or 'Not a valid ICMP code'.

Also for validating ICMP 'type' and 'code' there wasn't any dedicated
functionality in 'oslo.utils/netutils' so the code for validating 'TCP
ports' was used. TCP ports are in range 0 to 65535 while ICMP 'type'
and 'code' are in range 0 to 255, so using 'TCP port validation' code
is incorrect.

Here newer dedicated functionality of 'oslo.utils/netutils' is used
for validating ICMP 'type' and ICMP 'code'.

Change-Id: I3c9debc0eb156a4a3932b5e3f4dd601a313d065e
Closes-Bug: #1511748
"}]
commit_message:
ICMP type & code validation while adding Security Group rules

While adding new 'Security Group Rule' viz. 'Custom ICMP rule' when
wrong ICMP 'type' or 'code' was given the errors it would show were
'Not a valid port number'; which is misleading. The errors should
rather be 'Not a valid ICMP type' or 'Not a valid ICMP code'.

Also for validating ICMP 'type' and 'code' there wasn't any dedicated
functionality in 'oslo.utils/netutils' so the code for validating 'TCP
ports' was used. TCP ports are in range 0 to 65535 while ICMP 'type'
and 'code' are in range 0 to 255, so using 'TCP port validation' code
is incorrect.

Here newer dedicated functionality of 'oslo.utils/netutils' is used
for validating ICMP 'type' and ICMP 'code'.

Change-Id: I3c9debc0eb156a4a3932b5e3f4dd601a313d065e
Closes-Bug: #1511748

commit_message:
Include l2gw_plugin.ini while starting Neutron server

The patch set fixes the problem in the l2gw devstack scripts
where the l2gw_plugin.ini file neither gets copied to /etc/neutron,
nor is supplied while starting the neutron server.

Change-Id: If519e1a5394954d14673302aa8792f27017f60fa
Closes-Bug: 1511614

[{'created': '2015-10-15 13:22:12.000000000', 'message': "[Reports] Add an option for embedding JS/CSS libs into report

This change allows running command `report' with `--static'
option so all required JS/CSS will be embedded to HTML file.
Having all required CSS/JS loaded directly from HTML makes
report working without access to the Internet.

IMPORTANT: This patch should be checked for possible issues
related with usage of added third-party files:
    rally/ui/templates/vendor/nv.d3.min.css
    rally/ui/templates/vendor/angular.min.js
    rally/ui/templates/vendor/nv.d3.min.js
    rally/ui/templates/vendor/d3.min.js

commit_message:
[Reports] Add an option for embedding JS/CSS libs into report

This change allows running command `report' with `--html-static'
option so all required JS/CSS will be embedded to HTML file.
Having all required CSS/JS loaded directly from HTML makes
report working without access to the Internet.

Added third-party libraries files:
    rally/ui/templates/libs/nv.d3.1.1.15-beta.min.css
    rally/ui/templates/libs/angular.1.3.3.min.js
    rally/ui/templates/libs/nv.d3.1.1.15-beta.min.js
    rally/ui/templates/libs/d3.3.4.13.min.js

Notes about licenses compatibility:
    https://angularjs.org/

commit_message:
Fix flavor quota charts in NG Launch Instance

The flavor quota charts aren't rendering correctly
when the instance count is changed in the Angular
Launch Instance modal. The <svg> element was not
available to add slices as 'chartData.showChart'
is originally undefined.

This patches fixes the the issue by using ng-show
instead of ng-if.

Change-Id: I7b24da7942c3d02a55adc732d70a26aeb5b623ec
Closes-Bug: #1518030

Add reno for release notes management

In addition to the convention of releasenotes/source directory
which used in most OpenStack project, we have the release notes
in our developer documents.

Change-Id: Ied07af5ee5c8929e639e17a34b559cebfe419dc4

Nova over to use o.vo's version of it.

commit_message:
[install] text clean up and clarifications in neutron-concepts

Removed redundant text about routers which is repeated later on. Also
removed text about DHCP being disabled on external networks as I believe
this is incorrect. Clarification on "network" that it's external networks
where gateways are.  A couple of cosmetic minor changes as well.

Closes-Bug: #1519457
Change-Id: I350616c1d187b8999d7ff33c322461d91ef14691

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

[{'created': '2015-03-12 08:37:02.000000000', 'message': "libvirt: optimize multipath call to identify IQN

When detaching a multipath volume in an environment where there are
many attached volumes, excessive multipath calls are generated and
it takes too much time. This issue is due to the fact that a multipath -ll
call against many multipath devices takes a few seconds.

When detaching a volume, the current _disconnect_volume_multipath_iscsi()
calls 'multipath -ll <each iscsi device>' against every iscsi devices.
This behavior is to identify the IQNs used by multipath device, however
the IQNs are extracted from one 'multipath -ll' call without massive
'multipath -ll <each iscsi device>' calls.

This patch changes the behavior of identifying IQNs used by multipath device:

  1. add an utility to identify IQNs by using multipath device map
     (/dev/sdX => /dev/mapper/XXX) generated by parsing 'multipath -ll'.
  2. replace the current nested for loop to identify the IQNs with
     the utility.

Change-Id: I77e6eda950726d7ee9a0d92882d4501e70a0d8f8
Closes-Bug: 1277316

commit_message:
libvirt: optimize multipath call to identify IQN

When detaching a multipath volume in an environment where there are
many attached volumes, excessive multipath calls are generated and
it takes too much time. This issue is due to the fact that a multipath -ll
call against many multipath devices takes a few seconds.

When detaching a volume, the current _disconnect_volume_multipath_iscsi()
calls 'multipath -ll <each iscsi device>' against every iscsi devices.
This behavior is to identify the IQNs used by multipath device, however
the IQNs are extracted from one 'multipath -ll' call without massive
'multipath -ll <each iscsi device>' calls.

This patch changes the behavior of identifying IQNs used by multipath device:

  1. add an utility to identify IQNs by using multipath device map
     (/dev/sdX => /dev/mapper/XXX) generated by parsing 'multipath -ll'.
  2. replace the current nested for loop to identify the IQNs with
     the utility.

Co-Authored-By: Pavel Kholkin <pkholkin@mirantis.com>

Change-Id: I77e6eda950726d7ee9a0d92882d4501e70a0d8f8
Closes-Bug: #1277316

commit_message:
Fix wait condition doc sample

The snippet used to demonstrate wait conditions was incorrect, as it was
trying to use get_attr on the data attribute, which is a string and not
a mapping. Fn::Select can be used to handle it.

Change-Id: Ic9083087a155a37b85c36c0c0cbb53b654fd8b5c

commit_message:
Remove 'trigger' from api layer

We don't want to support trigger abstraction in senlin because it is
determined that this is not within senlin's scope.

commit_message:
Use "/mnt/image" instead of "/mnt" to mount

In the image guide, it mkdir of /mnt/image without any use of it.
Mount the device to it.

Change-Id: I1f8f33acfb850d2e9baf412ce6453521f0783f5a

commit_message:
Use Tempest-lib's compute migrations_client

Compute migrations_client has been migrated to
tempest-lib- I0dbae04c479b9d742a3e51d1d60c372093c2c027

Now Tempest-lib provides this client as stable interface so Tempest
should start using this from lib and remove its own copy.
Also remove its unit tests.

This commits makes Tempest to use compute migrations_client
from Tempest-lib.

Change-Id: Ic969a9b10ce0157e1213f26960ba8bc70d974413

commit_message:
Remove the old fake server data.

The old fake server framework has be replaced with the new
class FakeServer, which is stronger in:
1. faking multiple servers with random names and ids
2. faking methods in a server
3. easier to use

So remove the old fake server data, and use class FakeServer
from now on.

Change-Id: Ife8ee37a7ce14d9a3201104bce8075a918a97613
Implements: blueprint osc-unit-test-framework-improvement

commit_message:
Drop fixed_network dependency from CONF

The fixed_network module has very little dependency from config;
removing it so that it may be used by the preprov_creds module.

Change-Id: I24de72a0a997d2824b72338e31fec5329d601074

BTW, one general point - we should not assume that "secure" migration will always require tunnelling via libvirt. We have a goal of enhancing QEMU so that it can directly use TLS over its migration data channel, removing the need to tunnel via libvirt. The main driving factor for that is to improve performance by removing many data copies from the architecture. So in future, Nova may be able to support encrypted migration without tunnelling.'}, {'account_id': 10218, 'date': '2014-04-22 16:43:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Daniel: Great news. 

From scratch in this BP I have tried to manage the encryption option to be independent of the underlying mechanism and the virtualization driver. (But to make sure it works for the currently available tunneled mechanism in libvirt.)

Where available I would appreciate any further details/links on this direct TLS migration approach. Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2014-04-22 17:17:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: (2 inline comments)

The user of the cloud usually has little-to-no information about the way in which it was deployed. As such they will have little basis from which to evaluate what threats the cloud infrastructure is exposed to. Thus I'd suggest a user of the cloud has no ability to make an intelligent decision on whether to use encryption or not for live migration. I just don't see that this is something that is suitable for exposing in the API."}, {'account_id': 9275, 'date': '2014-05-28 17:24:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

i think the bp aims to provide this feature to admin only.
 
Users as "cloud users" and not Admin/Operators, don't have access to this feature. 

I agree, it could be solved by config file or by using flavor specs, but still is a good feature for private clouds where the Admin can choose to migrate encrypted or not an specific VM. ( may depend on the data it handle , Ex: employee/bank data, etc)

If using flavor specs, we still need to handle that in code, right?'}, {'account_id': 10218, 'date': '2014-06-18 16:17:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thanks much for the feedback, comments below.

@John:

I am more interested in addressing the case where admins have missed the encrypted Live Migration file configuration, than on the possibility to disable this option on demand.

I find this BP may better help in cases where the admin does not know/missed/forgot encrypted configuration in files, and plenty of nodes that require to be modified/restarted for enabling encryption afterwards.

That said, I still find some scenarios where it could be useful to disable the option on demand:
 
- Availability: current libvirt tunneling approach has a performance impact (given additional copies required), then this could not be acceptable for *Live* Migration.

- Performance: in case risks may be acceptable (i.e. private clouds, not sensitive information) an admin may require a fast migration of high number of nodes.

Besides it requires admin credentials I agree that allowing to disable encryption thru API could increase the attack surface. So in the trade-off it could be selected not to offer such flexibility for previous scenarios. In such a case, then it could only be offered the *enable* encryption option thru API (such a force-encrypted-migration option, for cases where not previously configured in nodes).

Referring to admins to "remember" the configuration, this could be addressed by setting "encrypted" as the default behavior and/or to take precedence on the configuration in files.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-18 16:17:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Verified

http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2014-07-01 17:56:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

I don't really see understand the use case you are presenting here.

Generally having a smaller API in Nova should be our goal, so I would all API additions to have a good reason to exist, and I just can't see the good reason here.

You might want to disable encryption on certain live-migrates, if you want to speed things up, but that doesn't really seem like a massively important use case, and its not the use case you are presenting here.

You might worry about inconsistent configuration between the compute nodes, which is fine, but moving that responsibility to the caller of the API is really the wrong approach. You probably want something in the compute api that tells the compute nodes they must use encryption. But that that point we are messing up bits of Nova that should really be fixed by good configuration management and config auditing, so I don't really think that should be Nova's job."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-01 17:58:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

@John:

Yes, I have removed in BP the ability to disable encryption given this may potentially increase the attack surface and that I agree this would not be a major use case.

The goal of the BP is then to allow admins to force encryption for cases where there is not appropriate/consistent configuration of nodes.
 
This does not conflict/neither impacts the current ability to configure encryption in nova.conf; this is just a complementary option for *admins* to tell compute nodes they *must* use encryption (i.e. if not configure to).

Possible use cases:
*  admins to force encryption via nova-client calls
*  admins to force encryption via Dashboard (adding this option in API allows to expose this in Horizon)
* Orchestrator components to force encryption in live migration calls.'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-07-02 09:42:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Force Encrypted Live Migration thru Nova API

The goal of this Blueprint is to allow admins to force "encrypted" Live
Migration (LM) thru Nova API. This will leverage and allow admins to use
encryption in Live Migrations everywhere; especially for cases where no
encryption has been set in configuration files and without the need to
manually update and restart nodes/services.

The proposal is to modify Nova API once for exposing this option for the
different virtualization drivers, and initially to implement this option for
libvirt driver making use of libvirt tunneling.

Related to blueprint: encrypted-live-migration-nova

Change-Id: I505404ffd973277948e538e3bc5ea5d7f297133e

commit_message:
Move development.environment.rst to standard location

According to [1], every project should publish instructions
for setting up a development environment to
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/<PROJECT_NAME>/devref/development.environment.html

Zaqar's development environment setup instructions are moved
there for consistency.

[1] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Getting_The_Code#Hacking_on_your_laptop_and_running_unit_tests

Change-Id: I45fb14a5777f3b639252b3ca4c3b7d114c23a332

commit_message:
Reimplement authenticate method in sdk driver

This patch reimplements authenticate method in senlin sdk driver
to use keystoneauth session interface to get access information.

Change-Id: I88912a8f868fb40ec6562ed94ad7dbe11c2a8f0e

commit_message:
Use class FakeServer in TestServerCreate.

In the current TestServerCreate, there are several problems:

1. The fake create() returns a server with no 'networks' field.
   The new_server is used to fake the created server which is
   supposed to be returned by create(), but it has a 'networks'
   field.

   They have the same name and id, but they are actually not
   the same server.

   As a result, when checking the return value from create(),
   'networks' is not checked.

2. The fake server is not accessable in the test functions.
   So each time a test function wants to get the server name
   or id, it has to use the constants defined in compute_fakes.

   This is not good. We should make the fake server accessable
   in all test functions to ensure they actually get the same
   server.

This patch fix them both by using the new class FakeServer to
fake a server.

Change-Id: I8ffc8e233f8710034329ed33fccb2c734898ec2d
Implements: blueprint osc-unit-test-framework-improvement

changeable.

commit_message:
LeftHand: Remove self.db assignment

DB access was removed in a previous patch when it was no longer
needed at the driver level. The self.db assignment was overlooked
and not removed, even though it is no longer being used.

Change-Id: Ic96c0ae96e78d3d2a0e2b99b7e1ca9461a7e7b27

commit_message:
Fixup oslo middleware to use new package name

oslo has deprecated using oslo.x package name and moved to use
oslo_x [1]. This fix helps to resolve tacker-server error
due to old reference

[1] https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/drop-namespace-packages

Change-Id: I62eb7cc7c68f5ff6bd7f0c4ec72d8be40e28b6b5

commit_message:
Limit version of Angular-Bootstrap

We are currently *only* compatible with version 0.11.0.2
of Angular-Bootstrap so we should pin that version. We can't
pin in OpenStack, so I'll use a more complex limiting
expression. This will allow the 0.13 version of that package
to be released without breaking Horizon (and migration to that
new version).

Change-Id: I64441baa8e9b00c273057d0fe8593120300e400d

commit_message:
Fix udev cinder issue

/run/udev contains the udev information needed for the lvm tools
/run and /dev must be bound in for this to work properly

Change-Id: Icfe07c4ce3673310cc24591b42c107c9710cd3ac
Closes-Bug: #1518454
Closes-Bug: #1487780
Related-Bug: #1487807
(cherry picked from commit 3cd5eec2ec7659c895e71d3eb7055694d59e125d)

The OpenStackClient mapping of 'openstack quota set' arguments isn't
correct for compute quota items that have to different names.  For
example, the --injected-file-size argument is mapped to
injected_file_size, but the compute quotas item is actually
injected_file_content_bytes.  This incorrect mapping prevented the
impacted compute quota items from being set.

The problem impacts the following 'openstack quota set' arguments:
  --injected-file-size
  --injected-path-size
  --properties
  --secgroup-rules
  --secgroups

This patch set also expands the compute quota unit tests to verify
all compute quota items that can be set.

"}]
commit_message:
Unable to set some compute quotas

The OpenStackClient mapping of 'openstack quota set' arguments isn't
correct for compute quota items that have to different names.  For
example, the --injected-file-size argument is mapped to
injected_file_size, but the compute quotas item is actually
injected_file_content_bytes.  This incorrect mapping prevented the
impacted compute quota items from being set.

The problem impacts the following 'openstack quota set' arguments:
  --injected-file-size
  --injected-path-size
  --properties
  --secgroup-rules
  --secgroups

This patch set also expands the compute quota unit tests to verify
all compute quota items that can be set.

Change-Id: I0a2f241e425f4811e4ae55be183ac0c8b0805c2a
Closes-Bug: #1475831

commit_message:
Fix swap_volume for case without migration

Fix swap_volume so that even when a volume-migration does not
occur, the volumes don't get stuck in "attaching" and "detaching".
Previously the swap_volume was changed in
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/101932 and
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/101933 to move the final
attach and detach logic to Cinder, however those changes only fix
the migration path.  This change calls Cinder's "attach" and "detach"
for the non-migration path to update the volumes' states.

Change-Id: I242c2c7c4a7197bbce04d0b3d75688f989ea1fd5
Closes-Bug: #1489744
(cherry picked from commit dc777f1dc736b01b8f8eec58972230d30b3074f6)

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-15 16:40:28.000000000', 'message': 'Handle cinder v2

It turns out that cinder v2 has a service_type of volumev2 because
nobody thought of the children. But that's ok - we actually care about
user experience around here. SO - take the sane approach and return
service_type = volumev2 if service_type == volume and volume_api_version
== 2. This way user code can all safely say "please give me the endpoint
for the volume service" and can use the api_version parameter to specify
which version they want.

We should all possess righteous indignation about this patch.

Change-Id: I15fc5ddd92345d78b6928f11a8d77cecd0427f7d
'}, {'created': '2015-11-24 23:28:28.000000000', 'message': 'Handle cinder v2

nobody thought of the children. But that's ok - we actually care about

service_type = volumev2 if service_type == volume and volume_api_version
== 2. This way user code can all safely say "please give me the endpoint
for the volume service" and can use the api_version parameter to specify
which version they want.

We should all possess righteous indignation about this patch.

Change-Id: I15fc5ddd92345d78b6928f11a8d77cecd0427f7d
'}]
commit_message:
Handle cinder v2

It turns out that cinder v2 has a service_type of volumev2 because
nobody thought of the children. But that's ok - we actually care about
user experience around here. SO - take the sane approach and return
service_type = volumev2 if service_type == volume and volume_api_version
== 2. This way user code can all safely say "please give me the endpoint
for the volume service" and can use the api_version parameter to specify
which version they want.

We should all possess righteous indignation about this patch.

Change-Id: I15fc5ddd92345d78b6928f11a8d77cecd0427f7d

commit_message:
Do not use api-paste.ini osprofiler options

Starting with opsrofiler 0.3.1 release there is no need to set HMAC_KEYS
and ENABLED arguments in the api-paste.ini file, this can be set in the
trove.conf configuration file.

Change-Id: Icbeb8bb09536bad88907fe590fa70386199ce03d

Add code-review devref for release notes

Now that we use reno, we need to provide some docs for explaining when
to provide a reno file.

Change-Id: Iebdbdad11986726aeebbf8fdc27e8dbe0bffb299

commit_message:
Add python consul client

This client library is used to interact with Consul. Consul
driver will be added to Tooz drivers.

Is the library actively maintained?
  Yes, cablehead seems to be the guy who is maintaining
  it. This library is just a wrapper around python requests
  module (https://github.com/cablehead/python-consul).
Is the library good code?
  Yes.
Is the library python 3 compatible?
  Yes.
Is the library license compatible?
  Yes.
Is the library already packaged in the distros we target?
  Yes.
Is the function of this library already covered by other
libraries in global-requirements.txt?
  Nope

Change-Id: I4f57a2f37f268a66b29b81a9401c1a2edba1fe7a

commit_message:
Add "openstack server shelve" into OSC

Currently, the shelve operation is not supported by OSC.
So, this patch attempts to add it into OSC.

Change-Id: I92545300bef006a069338168d2de800e8a58af69
Implements: blueprint introduce-shelve-into-osc

(3 comments)

Just a few nits, but concern about dropping conf options w/o deprecating them first.   I'd suggest leaving the option in there, log a warning at startup that the option is going away in the next release, and then ignore it.

Also, for what it's worth, the multipath flag is passed in from nova into the connector object in initialize_connection.

If that flag is True, that means that nova.conf is configured to enable multipath, and that the daemon is running on the host.  This comes from os-brick here:
https://github.com/openstack/os-brick/blob/master/os_brick/initiator/connector.py#L121-L123"}, {'account_id': 8912, 'date': '2015-11-19 21:59:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thanks for the feedback, I'll update so we log the deprecated warning to let the user know.

The "multipath" in the connector is good to know about, though I don't think it fixes this problem.  If if "multipath" is False, we're mapping all storage WWNNs and if we then return all in target_wwn, we still hit the stranded LUN issue after disconnecting cause Brick doesn't know to disconnect the other mapping.'}, {'account_id': 8912, 'date': '2015-11-19 22:52:13.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 11903, 'date': '2015-11-20 00:34:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

[{'created': '2015-11-12 16:36:25.000000000', 'message': "Remove *_multipath_enabled flag from IBM drivers

Remove the *_multipath_enabled from the FlashSystem and
Storwize/SVC driver. When enabled, this flag was intended to create
a single mapping between the compute node and the storage device for
FC connections. However, all available storage WWNNs were still being
mapped to the compute node, and instead enabling this flag was
causing a terminate_connection to not cleanup all LUN mappings
(because Nova did not know of all the target_wwns that were actually
mapped). This can be seen by enabling the flag, connecting a volume,
disconnecting the volume and observing the stray LUN mappings under
'/dev/disk/by-path'.

Currently we do not have a way to limit the storage WWNNs which are
mapped during a FC connection, so we will remove the config to fix
this broken behavior.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I0019c1e0c0dbb0cd48a7f389376480e7fa1b1e07

commit_message:
Deprecate *_multipath_enabled flag for IBM drivers

Deprecate the *_multipath_enabled from the FlashSystem and
Storwize/SVC driver. When enabled, this flag was intended to create
a single mapping between the compute node and the storage device for
FC connections. However, all available storage WWNNs were still being
mapped to the compute node, and instead enabling this flag was
causing a terminate_connection to not cleanup all LUN mappings
(because Nova did not know of all the target_wwns that were actually
mapped). This can be seen by enabling the flag, connecting a volume,
disconnecting the volume and observing the stray LUN mappings under
'/dev/disk/by-path'.

Currently we do not have a way to limit the storage WWNNs which are
mapped during a FC connection, so we will ignore the config to fix
this broken behavior, and then remove the config next release.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I0019c1e0c0dbb0cd48a7f389376480e7fa1b1e07
Closes-Bug: #1516778

commit_message:
Doc: Update and add IP address

Fix the 'ip floating' command documentation file name.
Add missing command list documentation for the 'ip fixed'
and 'ip floating pool' commands.  In addition, update the
command description and argument help to fix minor issues
and use consistent terminology.  And finally, cleanup the
Network command object formatting.

Currently, API job skips all tests because TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR is not set
properly. The environment variable was hardcoded to
/opt/stack/tempest/etc before, and since that's the location for tempest
configuration files that was used in gate, it worked fine there.

But after we were forced to remove the hardcoded value from the file due
to regression in tox 2.2.0+ (If3742b6eabe295a5aaeb4901c55909a70c451698),
it was neither hardcoded, nor passed from the external gate environment.

Note that since tox 2.0.0, the tool does not pass all envvars into tox
targets, but require explicit specification of the list of variables
that should be allowed into the target environment, using passenv
directive.

api tox target, which should be enough to make the API job avoid
skipping all tests.

they want to execute the suite locally.

commit_message:
tox: pass TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR envvar into api target environment

Currently, API job skips all tests because TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR is not set
properly. The environment variable was hardcoded to
/opt/stack/tempest/etc before, and since that's the location for tempest
configuration files that was used in gate, it worked fine there.

But after we were forced to remove the hardcoded value from the file due
to regression in tox 2.2.0+ (If3742b6eabe295a5aaeb4901c55909a70c451698),
it was neither hardcoded, nor passed from the external gate environment.

Note that since tox 2.0.0, the tool does not pass all envvars into tox
targets, but require explicit specification of the list of variables
that should be allowed into the target environment, using passenv
directive.

So that's what the patch does: it allows TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR to get into
api tox target, which should be enough to make the API job avoid
skipping all tests.

Users are still required to set TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR variable locally if
they want to execute the suite locally.

Closes-Bug: #1518632
Change-Id: Ia7dcc6785390a6012c7ba16a14573aa44f2b6fb5
(cherry picked from commit 143b3dc2864bec1f92eeed44a351e420ae68fd58)

A few remarks to signal my point of view.

Generally this is rather clean-up work and as it does a lot of RPC changes it will make code even harder to understand when we'll make it backward compatible. Probability of making this more buggy than it is now is high IMO.

I would say that we should skip this cleanup in Mitaka. We're trying to achieve rolling upgrades and this may be tricky to get right as we don't have a lot of experience with upgradeability. In N we should be able to have some partial grenade testing to make sure this works.

I would even sign up for broader quotas code cleanup in N."}, {'account_id': 8846, 'date': '2015-11-17 02:36:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1

Hi Michal, just to clarify for me, what did you mean when you said this would make code harder to understand / probably more buggy? I'm fine with the possibility of holding off on this if it's an issue until N, but the concept of moving the quota checks to the API and then passing reservations through RPC to the manager doesn't seem like it's too complex. Sorry, I'm just trying to understand what negative impact it might have on the existing codebase. Thanks for the comments/advice throughout."}, {'account_id': 11600, 'date': '2015-11-20 18:03:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 12: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

One more issue on versioning - you need also to bump individual method's versions.

My concerns are based on the fact that in M we're trying to make rolling upgrades happen. Rolling upgrades is all about interoperability of the services between releases. In this case we need to care that Liberty's services can talk with Mitaka's (and vice versa). We don't have much experience with maintaining RPC compatibility so I'm looking at all the changes in this matter with a suspicious eye. Moreover we don't have any Grenade CI tests to actually test that in the gate.

This is nothing personal, just a lot of RPC API changes scare me. ;)

I'll review your patch more carefully through the weekend or on Monday."}, {'account_id': 17275, 'date': '2015-11-20 18:38:04.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 13.'}, {'account_id': 17275, 'date': '2015-11-20 18:40:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13:

commit_message:
Move quota checks from manager to API

Currently quotas are sometimes checked in cinder.volume.manager,
and other times checked in cinder.volume.api. This patch aims to
make these checks more consistent by moving calls from the manager
to the API. This way, we can give the user feedback before launching
the RPC call.

Change-Id: Ic7ea69ca8474749304fd329f326db248ef52555b
Closes-bug: #1508249

This commit adds a temporary version cap on subunit2sql to be < 1.0.0.
The 1.0.0 release includes a very large database migration which will
be slow to execute. The python DB api from >=v1.0.0 will not work with
a database that doesn't have the updated schema. So while the migration
is running let's cap the version we install to prevent everything from
breaking while the migration is running. (which might take days)

Change-Id: Iab89beb5c7aba8b744a62f5063e513b72cab0ec2
"}]
commit_message:
Set a temporary cap on subunit2sql before 1.0.0 release

This commit adds a temporary version cap on subunit2sql to be < 1.0.0.
The 1.0.0 release includes a very large database migration which will
be slow to execute. The python DB api from >=v1.0.0 will not work with
a database that doesn't have the updated schema. So while the migration
is running let's cap the version we install to prevent everything from
breaking while the migration is running. (which might take days)

Change-Id: Iab89beb5c7aba8b744a62f5063e513b72cab0ec2

commit_message:
find_security_group_rule does not find by name

The find_security_group_rule proxy documents that a security
group rule can be found by name or ID.  However, security
group rules do not have names.  This patch set corrects the
documentation.

Change-Id: I06f324ace50c2ce377263727e6a6bed6e4128c93
Closes-Bug: #1464362

commit_message:
boot-from-volume and network params for server create

Two of the more complex arguments for server creation are booting from
volume and attaching to specific networks. It's possible to add some
syntactic sugage to the constructor to make this work in a less insane
way.

Change-Id: Icdfd15c0c6ada79cee0fb15a31e1cb727869d215

commit_message:
Fix api_server agent test that broke due to a dep change

The test was slightly incorrect to begin with, but the issue didn't
become apparent until the oslo.log update from 1.13.0 to 2.0.0 for
whatever reason. open() raises IOError() not Exception() so it was not
being handled properly.

Also taking this opportunity to standardize the use of builtins to
match our other tests.

Change-Id: Idab637b09e8a437333f810f82f45b3e9c027dfdd

commit_message:
Reset stack status even when lock engine_id is None

Having a stack which is wedged UPDATE_IN_PROGRESS due to another bug,
restarting heat-engine should have resulted in the stack being reset to
UPDATE_FAILED. However the reset was skipped because the lock engine_id
was None.

This change removes the engine_id check since it is possible in practice
for an UPDATE_IN_PROGRESS stack to not be locked.

Since it is possible for the stack to change state in the unlocked
window, a check is added that the stack is still IN_PROGRESS before the
reset is performed.

Change-Id: I1739ccbdf75af35aac5be16b99200975df58b8e2
Closes-Bug: #1514615
(cherry picked from commit 44b2f0965dd329cf45a151705b0648819acff8c7)
