commit_message:
modify openstackclient functional tests to use neutron dsvm

OSC is finally getting ramped up to create neutron support, to do
so effectively, we want to create functional tests, so switch our
functional test job to use neutron.

I opted to directly change the job and avoid adding a second experimental
job. The chances of this breaking OSC is very low, and affects only
functional test code. If the gate does break we can simply skip the
tests that are affected so the gate is passing again.

Change-Id: I88972f535d3b10326c3e848d569d2e93564898f0

[{'account_id': 15967, 'date': '2015-11-03 08:42:21.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-03 08:47:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-kuryr-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/34/241134/1/check/gate-kuryr-pep8/7f31427/ : SUCCESS in 1m 47s

- gate-kuryr-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/34/241134/1/check/gate-kuryr-python27/b96f234/ : SUCCESS in 2m 22s'}, {'account_id': 11343, 'date': '2015-11-04 12:11:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I am trying to understand why this happens, its Neutron that allocate the IP when we create the port and Neutron should not try to allocate the same ip as the one used for the DHCP port.

Can you please explain how you encounter this bug?'}, {'account_id': 1923, 'date': '2015-11-04 22:46:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I don't see why this may be a problem if the IP allocation is done by Neutron. Are you seeing this when the default IPAM driver is used? If that's the case, the solution will be different as discussed earlier. Anyway, there may be cases where we have dhcp enabled (either the case where we use an existing Neutron network and we don't have an option to choose whether dhcp is enabled or not or if at some point we want to cover the case of mixing containers and VMs on the same network).

On the other hand, for cases where we create the network/subnet for containers only we won't need dhcp enabled. Could the solution be having this as a config option for all subnets? Using labels on a case by case basis may be an overkill but something we may explore later."}, {'account_id': 15967, 'date': '2015-11-05 04:07:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Gal:

Ip is being allocated by default IPAM driver of libnetwork. As we dont have kuryr ipam driver at present, so we dont have any choice other than using default ipam driver, until kuryr ipam driver is not there.
Earlier no ip was coming from libnetwork so ip allocation part was being handled by neutron but with built-in ipam, kuryr is honoring libnetwork request of allocated ip but built-in ipam dont have any idea that dhcp namespace has consumed one ip. HTH.


@Banix,
Right Banix, there will be no problem if ip allocation is by neutron but that is not possible until we dont have kuryr's own "null" remote ipam driver. As we discussed, I am working on implementation of https://blueprints.launchpad.net/kuryr/+spec/remote-ipam-driver. Incrementally we can make kuryr ipam driver to use neutron's pluggable ipam model.

I liked your suggestion of making it configurable. Current changes(always disabled) will not work once null ipam driver is there but with configuration option it could be enabled or disabled on will. Thanks for the nice suggestion.'}, {'account_id': 4395, 'date': '2015-11-06 06:53:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Ah I see, if neutron isn't allocating the ip_address but docker is it makes sense that we can to disable dhcp otherwise you'll run into what vikas is saying."}, {'account_id': 15967, 'date': '2015-11-10 10:14:05.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-10 10:30:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-kuryr-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/34/241134/2/check/gate-kuryr-pep8/b30321c/ : SUCCESS in 1m 51s
- gate-kuryr-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/34/241134/2/check/gate-kuryr-docs/09f7f55//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 2m 00s
- gate-kuryr-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/34/241134/2/check/gate-kuryr-python27/dfb06c7/ : SUCCESS in 2m 09s'}, {'account_id': 8279, 'date': '2015-11-10 16:02:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 9820, 'date': '2015-11-13 12:05:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6598, 'date': '2015-11-16 09:32:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 8279, 'date': '2015-11-16 09:45:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 6598, 'date': '2015-11-16 09:49:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 15967, 'date': '2015-11-16 10:46:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 15967, 'date': '2015-11-16 10:50:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Irena,

Will it work with DHCP=TRUE or not, will depend on whether ipam is aware about ip consumed by dhcp port or not. With default built-in ipam driver, it will not work. But with some other ipam implementation, it may work. So to me it makes sense to have it configurable.

Thoughts?'}, {'account_id': 6598, 'date': '2015-11-16 12:21:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 12069, 'date': '2015-11-16 13:07:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

At this point, Kuryr doesn't work along with Docker's default IPAM if the DHCP port is enabled. So it's confusing to have the option for the DHCP port. Users can happen to make it enabled and it doesn't work. So it'd be better to just say Kuryr doesn't support the DHCP port for now explicitly."}, {'account_id': 15967, 'date': '2015-11-16 15:29:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Taku,

If i understood you correctly, you are suggesting to disable dhcp via hardcoding and not providing any configuration option.
If user is not sure he should go with default configuration and that we have 'disabled'. IMHO, it would still prefer current changes.

Thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 8279, 'date': '2015-11-17 04:39:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 14352, 'date': '2015-11-19 13:30:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

@all: I see this as a temporary fix for the bug while we let Docker's libnetwork do the network allocation and I am fine with it.

The real fix will come when we use neutron as the ipam driver for libnetwork. Then on container creation docker will ask kuryr, kuryr will request Neutron and there won't be conflict with dhcp or routers."}, {'account_id': 14352, 'date': '2015-11-19 13:33:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 14352, 'date': '2015-11-19 13:34:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

But I am not against this patch just not making configurable and disabling it if people find it less confusing. It works for me either way.'}, {'account_id': 15967, 'date': '2015-11-20 13:08:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@All,

Even after implementing kuryr ipam driver and making dhcp enabled by default, user will have option to use built-in ipam of docker. If dhcp is configurable it can be disabled and it will work fine. 
So IMO, having it configurable will be a better choice. Comments please.'}, {'account_id': 8279, 'date': '2015-11-20 14:43:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

Sure. Considering this is a stop gap solution, I am okay with it.'}, {'account_id': 11343, 'date': '2015-11-24 06:46:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

Looks good to me that this is configurable and that our default is False (as True doesnt currently work)

Maybe we should add a better explanation/comment next to the config to make sure users understand why is it set like that (and hopefully be more cautious about changing it)'}, {'account_id': 6598, 'date': '2015-11-24 07:36:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

Given  others' comments, I will remove -1. But I am not convinced that this patch provides proper treatment for the dhcp=True, so leaving this option to be configurable seems not very useful. Adding explanations why if set to True will have a lot of limitations, just proves it."}, {'account_id': 1923, 'date': '2015-11-24 18:48:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

As stated and agreed on during weekly call, this is a stop gap solution only. I do not see the option of using the default driver with dhcp disabled a possible solution we want to have after we have a null ipam driver. 
Not merging to see if Taku is ok with this.'}, {'account_id': 14352, 'date': '2015-11-24 21:50:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Workflow+1

Let's merge this for now. We can improve once we have the IPAM driver."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-24 21:50:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Verified

commit_message:
Create subnets with dhcp disabled

This fix is intended to disable dhcp for subnets created. If dhcp is
enabled, driver has no information about ip address allocated to dhcp
namespace interface and eventually tries to allocate same ip address to
container and this leads to exception from neutron saying "The IP
address is in use."

Change-Id: If598cacb475ab442108f2176310c8468e09d793f
Closes-Bug: #1512341

This commit adds a temporary version cap on subunit2sql to be < 1.0.0.
The 1.0.0 release includes a very large database migration which will
be slow to execute. The python DB api from >=v1.0.0 will not work with
a database that doesn't have the updated schema. So while the migration
is running let's cap the version we install to prevent everything from
breaking while the migration is running. (which might take days)

Change-Id: Ieadcc6847a1648bc247fd840ec95653f438be664
"}]
commit_message:
Add a temporary version cap on subunit2sql

This commit adds a temporary version cap on subunit2sql to be < 1.0.0.
The 1.0.0 release includes a very large database migration which will
be slow to execute. The python DB api from >=v1.0.0 will not work with
a database that doesn't have the updated schema. So while the migration
is running let's cap the version we install to prevent everything from
breaking while the migration is running. (which might take days)

Change-Id: Ieadcc6847a1648bc247fd840ec95653f438be664

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-24 19:09:13.000000000', 'message': "tox: pass TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR envvar into api target environment

Currently, API job skips all tests because TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR is not set
properly. The environment variable was hardcoded to
/opt/stack/tempest/etc before, and since that's the location for tempest
configuration files that was used in gate, it worked fine there.

But after we were forced to remove the hardcoded value from the file due
to regression in tox 2.2.0+ (If3742b6eabe295a5aaeb4901c55909a70c451698),
it was neither hardcoded, nor passed from the external gate environment.

Note that since tox 2.0.0, the tool does not pass all envvars into tox
targets, but require explicit specification of the list of variables
that should be allowed into the target environment, using passenv
directive.

So that's what the patch does: it allows TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR to get into
api tox target, which should be enough to make the API job avoid
skipping all tests.

Users are still required to set TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR variable locally if
they want to execute the suite locally.

Conflicts:
	tox.ini

Closes-Bug: #1518632
Change-Id: Ia7dcc6785390a6012c7ba16a14573aa44f2b6fb5
(cherry picked from commit 143b3dc2864bec1f92eeed44a351e420ae68fd58)
"}]
commit_message:
tox: pass TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR envvar into api target environment

Currently, API job skips all tests because TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR is not set
properly. The environment variable was hardcoded to
/opt/stack/tempest/etc before, and since that's the location for tempest
configuration files that was used in gate, it worked fine there.

But after we were forced to remove the hardcoded value from the file due
to regression in tox 2.2.0+ (If3742b6eabe295a5aaeb4901c55909a70c451698),
it was neither hardcoded, nor passed from the external gate environment.

Note that since tox 2.0.0, the tool does not pass all envvars into tox
targets, but require explicit specification of the list of variables
that should be allowed into the target environment, using passenv
directive.

So that's what the patch does: it allows TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR to get into
api tox target, which should be enough to make the API job avoid
skipping all tests.

Users are still required to set TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR variable locally if
they want to execute the suite locally.

Conflicts:
	tox.ini

Closes-Bug: #1518632
Change-Id: Ia7dcc6785390a6012c7ba16a14573aa44f2b6fb5

commit_message:
V1: Stop id changes after the image creation

Currently in v1 if someone tries to update the ID after the image is
created it will cause a 500 to be returned (or if updating to the same
ID a 200). This now returns a 403.

ApiImpact

Change-Id: Ibb40632f027b2b84f88aaf0a971a0f18de350187
Closes-Bug: 1483353

commit_message:
Update os.path.remove as it does not exist

Os.path.remove does not exist so this removes it and replaces it with
some code that will remove the file. Functionally fulfilling the role
that os.path.remove was meant to fill.

Change-Id: I040d445007055b31561a592dd74b3e2ffaa9cd54
Closes-bug: 1507564

of scenarios and environment configurations.

---
 section_name:
   env:
     common_env_name: ["args1", "args2"]
   tasks:
    - file: task-filename.yaml
      env:
        local_env_name: ["variant1", "variant2"]

Sample manifest file:

---
  nova:
    env:
      keystone: ["v2.0", "v3"]
    tasks:
      - file: rally-jobs/nova-1.yaml
      - file: rally-jobs/nova-2.yaml
  keystone:
    tasks:
      - file: rally-jobs/keystone-v2-only-scenarios.yaml
        env:
          keystone: ["v2.0"]
  rally:
    tasks:
      - file: rally-jobs/rally-dummy-scenarios.yaml
        env:
          keystone: ["v2.0", "v3"]
          rally: ["0.0.3", "0.0.4"]

Please note: in the latest section of sample manifest file
the scenario will be ran 4 times:

 keystone v2 + rally 0.0.3
 keystone v2 + rally 0.0.4
 keystone v3 + rally 0.0.3
 keystone v3 + rally 0.0.4

Manifest filename may be specified via RALLY_MANIFEST
environment variable.
If variable is missing then script will try to open
rally-scenarios/manifest.yaml or rally-jobs/manifest.yaml.
If file still does not exist then legacy behavior will be used.

commit_message:
Add new script for rally-gate jobs

This script does support manifest file with list
of scenarios and environment configurations.

Manifest is yaml file of following format:

---
 section_name:
   env:
     common_env_name: ["args1", "args2"]
   tasks:
    - file: task-filename.yaml
      env:
        local_env_name: ["variant1", "variant2"]

Sample manifest file:

---
  nova:
    env:
      keystone: ["v2.0", "v3"]
    tasks:
      - file: rally-jobs/nova-1.yaml
      - file: rally-jobs/nova-2.yaml
  keystone:
    tasks:
      - file: rally-jobs/keystone-v2-only-scenarios.yaml
        env:
          keystone: ["v2.0"]
  rally:
    tasks:
      - file: rally-jobs/rally-dummy-scenarios.yaml
        env:
          keystone: ["v2.0", "v3"]
          rally: ["0.0.3", "0.0.4"]

Please note: in the latest section of sample manifest file
the scenario will be ran 4 times:

 keystone v2 + rally 0.0.3
 keystone v2 + rally 0.0.4
 keystone v3 + rally 0.0.3
 keystone v3 + rally 0.0.4

Manifest filename may be specified via RALLY_MANIFEST
environment variable.
If variable is missing then script will try to open
rally-scenarios/manifest.yaml or rally-jobs/manifest.yaml.
If file still does not exist then legacy behavior will be used.

Change-Id: Ice85a94abb9ac7267a1ae9fb41b480adaf58b4b6

commit_message:
Workaround eventlet bug with subunit on python 3

This commit adds a workaround to the testr.conf which simply pipes the
output of the test command through cat to ensure we don't end up with
partial writes in the subunit stream. Without this we can potentially
end up with an incomplete write in the subunit stream which results
in a broken stream. This issues has been documented upstream in both
eventlet [1] and subunit [2] and the fixes will likely happen soon,
but in the meantime we need to workaround the issue.

[1] https://github.com/eventlet/eventlet/issues/248
[2] https://github.com/testing-cabal/subunit/pull/14

Change-Id: Ia4294cdd5e5873fca8bdb9cd97c8c37ad0c88471

commit_message:
Add a warning for new mitaka releases of oslo.messaging

Neutron (and possibly others) were/are using a private symbol of
oslo.messaging  several reviews have been put in place to mitigate this
including a requirements change that bans
!=2.6.0,!=2.6.1,!=2.7.0,!=2.8.0,!=2.8.1,!=2.9.0 from liberty

If a new release is tagged in the range >2.6.0 <3.0.0 it will NOT be
banned and may introduce a regression.

A release in that range is doable but we need to be careful.  Add a
warning to that we don't forget and do that thing.

Depends-On: I5d15366a212c6ed21f33bfe011876fc2bb56997c
Change-Id: Ia7cdbbed5e529864e751add6af05e5fc0be963e1

commit_message:
Remove periods of docstring

Based on the desgin of openstack client, the docstring of each
function will be the help string for cli. Now all the other
services' commands don't use a period. So let's remove them
for zaqar to be consistent.

Change-Id: I9c8b18995c311d844a25c4a4da6be1aa6cc3790b

commit_message:
Rationalize list role assignment routing

The v3 role assignment controller was created as a standard
controller even though it only supports the list method. This means
not only do we have code stubs that are unused, but this will
complicate the addition of separate entry points for listing role
assignments for a tree in the follow on patch.

This patch, therfore, rationalizes the routes so that this
is set up for just the list method, and removes the unused code
stubs.

Implements: bp list-assignment-subtree
Change-Id: I0c03accecdcf1608b50ad6b130c8a49d8a9b5b42

[{'created': '2015-11-23 18:46:10.000000000', 'message': 'Disable automatic config file discovery for pep8 target

When trying to run pep8 target on a system with installed
/etc/neutron/neutron.conf file, neutron-db-manage may fail due to
access denied to the configuration file. This is because oslo.config
attempts to discover configuration files automatically if they are
not passed with --config-file argument.

To disable auto discovery, we pass --config-file to the tool.

Change-Id: I89b5cbae1fcbf662cba6bc724681d0cfeeb0eb9c
(cherry picked from commit ae573d11bcb27d8ae17ddb25794d2d3e5fdd4438)
'}]
commit_message:
Disable automatic config file discovery for pep8 target

When trying to run pep8 target on a system with installed
/etc/neutron/neutron.conf file, neutron-db-manage may fail due to
access denied to the configuration file. This is because oslo.config
attempts to discover configuration files automatically if they are
not passed with --config-file argument.

To disable auto discovery, we pass --config-file to the tool.

Change-Id: I89b5cbae1fcbf662cba6bc724681d0cfeeb0eb9c
(cherry picked from commit ae573d11bcb27d8ae17ddb25794d2d3e5fdd4438)

commit_message:
Unify on _schedule_instances

There's already a helper method for unshelve_instance. It turns out
that the other two places in this file which call select_destinations
can use the same helper. Doing this removes some code redundancy.

I haven't pushed build_request_spec in as well because for bp
check-destination-on-migrations we won't always be constructing a
brand new request spec.

Change-Id: I19bad96d997f61958e32f6254bc4a428395bc7ec

We don't want to do this, because it prevents any project from using the library. Just because we don't need it doesn't mean we should prevent it from being installed. Cliff now checks at runtime whether to use unicodecsv or not, so it's safe to install and ignore it.

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/226966"}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-11-24 20:11:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Doug Hellmann: "Cliff now checks at runtime whether to use unicodecsv or not, so it's safe to install and ignore it."

Hum, it's just useless to install unicodecsv dependency on Python 3 if the csv of the stdlib is used :-/

It takes 4 lines to use csv on Python 3 and unicodecsv on Python 2.'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-11-24 20:18:12.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

lifeless wrote on another change: "so, I think you've misunderstood things here. The unicodecsv stuff was *not related to the 3.5 issue*. Doug put that in as a dependent change but the actual bug was only the class docstring lookup stuff. So this is fine."

Oh ok. Well, I don't want to spend time on this issue, so I just give up :-p'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-20 08:16:35.000000000', 'message': "Don't install unicodecsv on Python 3

On Python 3, the stdlib csv module handles well Unicode. There is no
need to use a third-party module for that.

Moreover, it looks like unicodecsv caused issues on Ubuntu with
Python 3.5 in the cliff library: see related bug.

Add also unicodecsv license.

Related-Bug: 1491888
Change-Id: Ie8fc1b00f4e76cfd5a81615d26ea7c05fdee7209
"}]
commit_message:
Don't install unicodecsv on Python 3

On Python 3, the stdlib csv module handles well Unicode. There is no
need to use a third-party module for that.

Moreover, it looks like unicodecsv caused issues on Ubuntu with
Python 3.5 in the cliff library: see related bug.

Add also unicodecsv license.

Related-Bug: 1491888
Change-Id: Ie8fc1b00f4e76cfd5a81615d26ea7c05fdee7209

commit_message:
Add check_uptodate.sh --checkopts to "pep8"

2f9e416 Downstream Fix for Genconfig
  collided with
fb17ed8 Add -constraints for CI jobs

while merging and this only got added to
pep8-constraints.  It should be in "pep8" as well.

opts.py is updated here since it is out of sync,
due to this test not running.

Change-Id: I668df6be4301a052a4b47549c702a81b43abd8fc

commit_message:
Correctly determine when SSL termination config changes

The Rackspace::Cloud::Loadbalancer resource does not diff
different versions of sslTermination config correctly, leading
it to be stuck in check_create_complete forever. This patch has
the required logic to make that check correctly.

Change-Id: I2fc3e9bf144f15a4bc48ad3996b8dde3338d361c
Closes-Bug: #1519069

os-win is a library containing Windows / Hyper-V code commonly used in the
OpenStack projects: nova, cinder, ceilometer, networking-hyperv. The
library can be used in any other OpenStack projects where it is needed.

All code has been developed under an Apache 2.0 license and has no
restrictions on distribution or deployment. All os-win code is submitted
and reviewed through OpenStack Gerrit [1]. The os-win project maintains
a core team that approves all changes. Bugs are filed, reviewed and
tracked in Launchpad [4].

os-win integrates in several OpenStack projects and services. The project
uses Oslo libraries.

os-win was first informally proposed at the Nova Liberty mid-cycle meetup.
The project is standalone and it is not part of Oslo, as per Oslo's team
decision. [5]

The first major release of os-win will be tagged for Mitaka.

commit_message:
Adding os-win to OpenStack

os-win is a library containing Windows / Hyper-V code commonly used in the
OpenStack projects: nova, cinder, ceilometer, networking-hyperv. The
library can be used in any other OpenStack projects where it is needed.

All code has been developed under an Apache 2.0 license and has no
restrictions on distribution or deployment. All os-win code is submitted
and reviewed through OpenStack Gerrit [1]. The os-win project maintains
a core team that approves all changes. Bugs are filed, reviewed and
tracked in Launchpad [4].

os-win integrates in several OpenStack projects and services. The project
uses Oslo libraries.

os-win was first informally proposed at the Nova Liberty mid-cycle meetup.
The project is standalone and it is not part of Oslo, as per Oslo's team
decision. [5]

The first major release of os-win will be tagged for Mitaka.

[1]: https://review.openstack.org/#/q/status:open+os-win,n,z
[2]: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Os-win
[3]: https://github.com/openstack/os-win
[4]: https://bugs.launchpad.net/os-win
[5]:
http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/oslo/2015/oslo.2015-08-17-16.00.log.html

Change-Id: Ib6f881b70bfeea68f264ec6f35a69befc55af823

Let me just say that the implementation here of joined table inh is very nicely done. 

Let me just first confirm what I'm seeing; we're taking several of the most key objects in Neutron, and altering the ORM mappings such that in order to load any of these objects, the load will first be against a table "neutron_resource" that right now has just a UUID primary key and a *single* column, which is essentially the discriminator.    The goal is that other columns like timestamps and such can be added to this common table rather than being added to all the subtables.


Unfortunately, this design is going perform very poorly and produce a lot of complexity, especially on MySQL/MariaDB oriented backends.  Joined table inheritance out of the box is going to get you much more highly composed and complex JOINs and subqueries immediately, which especially on MySQL perform terribly.   The JOIN here is also going to be against a 36 character string which will make for much heavier indexes.   Considering that Neutron is already very JOIN heavy (see https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1441790), we'd only want to use joined-table inheritance if there is a clear rationale.

So let's look at rationale.   The primary rationale of joined table inheritance is when a model deals primarily with the *base* entity, and for which the inherited subclasses are specializations of that entity.  Such as, the canonical example of Employee->(Manager, Engineer).   The HR department of a company really needs to deal with Employee objects 90% of the time, and then only in exception cases do they need to know the special things that are specific to Managers or Engineers.   Queries are against the Employee table in most cases.  Joined-table inheritance is designed around this use case.

In this case, the rationale is reversed; in all cases, we will be dealing here specifically with Subnet, Subnetpool, Network classes and objects directly; I haven't looked but I doubt we're going to have queries of the form `session.query(NeutronResouce).get('guid')`.  If we are, then that would be the reason to use joined-table inh.  But assuming that's not what we're doing here, the rationale is just that we'd like to reduce duplication of a certain set of columns that are common to many objects ("instead of being duplicated across each resource's table.").

That rationale is fine.  But let me introduce the concept that the duplication we're looking for here is in *source code*, not in the *schema*.  That is, by attempting to get the purely cosmetic effect of not actually having these common columns represented in the endpoint tables, we make everything more complicated, difficult, and slow.   We generally don't work with SQL and database schemas directly in Neutron since we use Python code with SQL abstraction layers, but if we did, the average database administrator who wanted to query the "port" table for when it was last updated would actually appreciate that the table had its own "timestamp" column, and not that they had to remember to make a JOIN out to another table.

As far as duplication of these columns in the source code, that's easy to fix, by just making NeutronResource a non-mapped declarative mixin class.

Which brings us to the last point involved here, which is that of schema migrations.   Now when we add a column to NeutronResource, we have to add it *everywhere*!  This is true.  But again, we are using tools for this, namely Alembic, where not only are the migrations automated but the generation of the scripts is automated as well.    You'd see a migration script that has four "ADD COLUMN" lines instead of one.   I don't think that's much of an issue.

So to sum up, unless the application sees itself moving towards a model where we are primarily going to be querying NeutronResource objects directly and receiving a polymorphic collection of objects back (in which case everything I've written here is wrong), I would strongly recommend we maintain these columns on each existing table individually rather than requiring a very JOIN-heavy change throughout the application.'}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-09-20 20:48:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

Thanks for the comment. Timestamps were a trivial use case since they don't have their own API to be queried all at once across different types so I shouldn't have used that as the example.

Take a look at the patch that depends on this one to see how the RBAC entries become significantly simplified by having a single table to query. RBAC has its own API to list all RBAC entries, create entries, etc. This means we have to query all of the RBAC tables via a big UNION query. However, this API will be hit much less frequently than queries to the ports, networks, etc so it's probably not worth the performance penalty you are implying."}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-09-20 21:02:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

How do you recommend we model cases where multiple types of resources will have a 0-to-many relationship with a new thing? Do we just continue with the pattern of duplicating the table schema for every object type?

For example, we are talking about adding tags to core resources. If we don't have a table like this we will need to add a tags table for every type of object that can be tagged."}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-09-21 14:52:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

> This means we have to query all of the RBAC tables via a big UNION query. 

so that is exactly the case *for* joined inheritance, when you want to query polymorphically which it seems is the case here.

> However, this API will be hit much less frequently than queries to the ports, networks, etc so it's probably not worth the performance penalty you are implying.


well if the queries for Port, Network etc. tend to be very simple lookups of one item, that wouldn't be too bad.  Things get crazy with joined inh if you have a lot of joined-eager loads from some parent object to say a Network collection. 

> For example, we are talking about adding tags to core resources. If we don't have a table like this we will need to add a tags table for every type of object that can be tagged.

So this is the polymorphic association pattern which I've written about for a long time; there's a suite illustrating all the different approaches to this at http://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/rel_1_0/orm/examples.html#module-examples.generic_associations.   For this case, it again depends on if you need to query for all NeutronResource objects with a certain set of tags (e.g. a query that would return a combination of types) or not.   If you didn't, then yes I do recommend having an association table per type."}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2015-09-23 15:02:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

I think the idea behind this patch is appropriate. There are a few improvements that I think could be made (see inline), but I note that substantial improvements to query performance would come from using integer keys on joined columns instead of the current long string-based UUID keys.'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2015-09-23 15:08:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

One other thing I wanted to note... the proposed central resources table here actually will not produce more complex composed joins. There will be an additional eq_join condition on the id columns from the central resources table to the spoke tables like networks, but the cost of that join is only a single in-memory lookup operation which is about the cheapest operation that exists in the optimizer (only const operations which generally can be optimized away are cheaper)...

Best,

-jay'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-09-23 15:52:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

OK.  if we could make the joins on a traditional int -> int foreign key, that would be very preferable to a string GUID.    I did a huge PG-GUID-joined-inh project some years ago, e.g. almost exactly this, and performance was a profound issue.'}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-09-23 23:15:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-10 08:58:09.000000000', 'message': "Make base Neutron objects reference single table

This adds a new 'neutronobjects' table and converts the IDs
of ports, subnets, networks, and subnetpools into foreign-key
references to this new table.

This will make it easy to add new things to the schema like
timestamp fields or anything else that applies to multiple types
of Neutron objects. The new fields would just be added to the
'neutronobjects' table instead of being duplicated across each
object's table.

This patch starts out with the 4 core resources to target the
timestamp patch that is currently being developed.

Change-Id: Iaa3ba81a7e9cae09cea153720b29879d8cc9a080

commit_message:
Make Neutron resources reference standard attr table

This adds a new 'standardattributes' table and adds a foreign-key
references from ports, subnets, networks, subnetpools, routers,
securitygroups, and floatingips to this table.

This will make it easy to add new things to the schema like
timestamp fields or anything else that applies to multiple types
of Neutron resources. The new fields would just be added to the
'neutronresources' table instead of being duplicated across each
resource's table. Or, if the the relationship is 1-to-many (e.g. tags),
the new association table would be related to the 'standardattribute'
table.

Related-Bug: #1496802
Change-Id: Iaa3ba81a7e9cae09cea153720b29879d8cc9a080

commit_message:
Retry API calls if they get a Retryable failure

keystoneauth1 Session throws exceptions based on
RetriableConnectionFailure when the operation can be sanely retried.
Since we have commuication encapsulated, there is no reason to not
just retry.

We should maybe in the future allow for configuration of number of
times to retry - but let's start with one and go from there.

Change-Id: Iacc6ac3d7eecbccfa7602fefb238602cc8a66cc4

Not sure if this is really broken, but we should sort it out before merging: if the code comments were true this patch would fail.

I'm looking at this one
https://github.com/openstack/django_openstack_auth/blob/master/openstack_auth/views.py#L102
which claims (more or less) that stuff we put into the session during authenticate won't be there later unless we stuff it into the User object and read it back out.  I've tested the code in my dev environment and it seems the comment is a lie.  Data I put into the session during authenticate remains and is available to Horizon.

Do we have any idea why the comment in views.py#L102 is there?  I'm wondering if older but supported versions of Django behave this way.  (I have 1.6.x)"}, {'account_id': 9981, 'date': '2015-03-06 00:20:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

A related, but less concrete concern, is that I think it would benefit us to tighten up the interface between django_openstack_auth and horizon.  Right now, the interface consists of both the User object (request.user) and the session data (request.session).  I thought everything had to be represented in the User object because of the comment in views.py#L102.  Even if that isn't true it seems needlessly complex to support both interfaces.  Is just writing directly to the session going to be our preferred approach?"}, {'account_id': 6162, 'date': '2015-03-06 20:40:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

I've posted a -1 on this not because there is anything wrong in the code as it is....however there is a new spec that looks like it will land in Liberty in Keystone that would allow the use of project scoped tokens to be used in place of domain scoped tokens for domain related operations. See: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/193543/

If this goes ahead, I don't think we will need this patch - since we will want people to use this project-scoped approach, rather than domain tokens - which I know is what a lot of people have been asking for.

The follow on patch (that creates the concepts of cloud/domain admin) would still be needed.

Let's liaise to see how best to synchronise these two efforts."}, {'account_id': 6162, 'date': '2015-06-26 15:32:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Hey Henry,

We are aware that there is work to combine the Domain scoped token with the Project scoped token.  Since that work is in progress and we haven't seen how it will integrate with horizon and current keystone v3 policy file we'd like to keep this effort moving forward.

Folks in keystone have assured us that Domain tokens as implemented today will continue to be supported along side the "dual scoped" token.

Once the "dual scoped" token work is complete we could come back and revisit this work to see if that would fit better than supporting two individual tokens.'}, {'account_id': 6162, 'date': '2015-06-26 15:32:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2015-06-26 16:52:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: -Code-Review

Dan - thanks for your comments, happy to remove -1.  You are correct that we will NOT be removing domain scoped tokens in Liberty. The keystone goal is to allow project scoped tokens to be used in their place in L, and the v3sample policy file will be changed to use these, rather than domain tokens. Nothing, however, should stop the current setup working.  Is there a config option to enable/disable the use of domain scoped tokens in Horizon?  If not, that might be sensible, since the hope is that our replacement project scoped token solution will "just work" with Horizon - so maybe having a toggle that directs which token type to request might be good.'}, {'account_id': 6162, 'date': '2015-06-26 18:07:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

Thanks Henry,

We'll work with you guys to try to make sure things don't lost.
Horizon does have a flag we use for multi domain support.

-Dan"}, {'account_id': 7179, 'date': '2015-06-26 20:02:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 1916, 'date': '2015-06-26 20:52:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review+1

to add some condiments to the domain versus project recipe ...

  1. Keystone V3 API is not going away and we are obligated to support domain-scoped token till V4.
  2. turn a domain into project has security concerns because
    a. domain-scoped token have no access to other OpenStack services whereas a project-scoped token can
    b. it will convolute project admin and service admin further. Not that bug 968696 isn't bad enough already.
    c. a project-scoped token will cause services who support auto-provision to create a bunch of ghost accounts which never will be utilized
  3. its hard enough to explain to my Grandma the difference between a project and a "special" project already, let along my paying customers
  4. Reseller requirements are murky at best right now.'}, {'account_id': 5623, 'date': '2015-06-26 21:27:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-12-11 20:34:00.000000000', 'message': "Add domain scoped token to session in multidomain

In order to perform identity operations in keystone v3 when multiple
domains are enabled, a domain scoped token is required. Adding the
domain scoped to the session as it remains valid until the user logs
out.

The domain scoped token is sizeable, so a check to make sure the
session backend used is not signed cookies, as this will overflow
the cookie.

Additionally, errors around getting and storing the domain scoped
token are logged, but doesn't block authentication, as it only blocks
identity operations.

A call to delete the domain token is made on logout.

Implements: blueprint domain-scoped-tokens
Change-Id: I0ed1737cdd80dc143f1df94700e311351d5d3b24

"}, {'created': '2015-02-04 17:21:10.000000000', 'message': "Add domain scoped token to session in multidomain

In order to perform identity operations in keystone v3 when multiple
domains are enabled, a domain scoped token is required. Adding the
domain scoped to the session as it remains valid until the user logs
out.

The domain scoped token is sizeable, so a check to make sure the
session backend used is not signed cookies, as this will overflow
the cookie.

Additionally, errors around getting and storing the domain scoped
token are logged, but doesn't block authentication, as it only blocks
identity operations.

A call to delete the domain token is made on logout.

Support for the case of a user with a domain role but no project roles
is now supported as well. That is a user can log in with only scoping
to a domain. This allows domain admins to be able to configure identity
without requiring a project role.

Implements: blueprint domain-scoped-tokens
Change-Id: I0ed1737cdd80dc143f1df94700e311351d5d3b24

policy file is used, a domain scoped token is required. Adding the
domain scoped token to the session as it remains valid until the user
logs out.

The domain scoped token is sizeable, so a check to make sure the
session backend used is not signed cookies, as this will overflow
the cookie.

Additionally, errors around getting and storing the domain scoped
token are logged, but doesn't block authentication, as it only blocks
identity operations.

Support for the case of a user with a domain role but no project roles
is now supported as well. That is a user can log in with only scoping
to a domain. This allows domain admins to be able to configure identity
without requiring a project role.

commit_message:
Add domain scoped token to session in multidomain

In order to perform identity operations in keystone v3 when the v3
policy file is used, a domain scoped token is required. Adding the
domain scoped token to the session as it remains valid until the user
logs out.

The domain scoped token is sizeable, so a check to make sure the
session backend used is not signed cookies, as this will overflow
the cookie.

Additionally, errors around getting and storing the domain scoped
token are logged, but doesn't block authentication, as it only blocks
identity operations.

A call to delete the domain token is made on logout.

Support for the case of a user with a domain role but no project roles
is now supported as well. That is a user can log in with only scoping
to a domain. This allows domain admins to be able to configure identity
without requiring a project role.

Implements: blueprint domain-scoped-tokens
Change-Id: I0ed1737cdd80dc143f1df94700e311351d5d3b24

commit_message:
Fix the scope of Kuryr in the devref

This patch changes "scope" attributes in the response of "docker network
inspect" command in libnetwork_remote_driver_design.rst. They were
"local" but they are supposed to be "global".

Change-Id: I4c4022a54e047f960182ec3f63286055a26d706d
Signed-off-by: Taku Fukushima <f.tac.mac@gmail.com>

tests: remove testscenario usage for storage drivers

We test only one driver at a time, so there is no need to leverage
scenarios here.

commit_message:
install openstack-heat-common in heat-base

the openstack-heat-common package installs the Heat UID/GID.
This is necessary pre-work for drop-root for heat services.

Change-Id: I247b0209248de144d20f5245973833be5cd8f14f
Partially-Implements: blueprint drop-root

commit_message:
python 2.7 support

python2.7, which is a default interpretator in CentOS 7
includes ordereddict module, so there is no need to declare
it as a dependency.

Change-Id: I01750fd766d2b00fce947ddf0824fe972804f1ad

commit_message:
Add exception handling for l3_clear_route

Sometimes l3_clear_route deletes old default route but at this moment
ubuntu hotplug has already changed(deleted and added new correct) it.

Change-Id: I5c0fe79871205aa355545c1e127c3cc72dc07904
Closes-bug: #1496307
(cherry picked from commit 94ae34d547c4173ccc0c88ed32a4d2caf0c7ab77)

subject: nova.network.linux_net refactor
messages:
[{'account_id': 6509, 'date': '2015-10-13 10:34:06.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-13 13:18:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-nova-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/16/234116/1/check/gate-nova-specs-docs/2362f8f//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 4m 18s
- gate-nova-specs-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/16/234116/1/check/gate-nova-specs-pep8/0d9bce7/ : SUCCESS in 1m 44s
- gate-nova-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/16/234116/1/check/gate-nova-specs-python27/a30097b/ : SUCCESS in 1m 54s'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-11-05 13:31:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I am not sure this is a fast approve.

We need to consider the OS VIF Lib effort that is looking to possibly extract this code from Nova. Getting the interface better is very helpful.'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2015-11-05 14:07:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

IIRC the linux_net code is used from two places - the VIF plugins and the nova-network code. 

With the VIF plugins moving to os-vif, it'll only leave the nova-network usage. If the FreeBSD port is intending to use Neutron, then it probably isn't worth refactoring linux_net in Nova. So we might just want to hold off on this until os-vif crystalizes"}, {'account_id': 6509, 'date': '2015-11-11 11:54:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hm, as for Neutron vs nova-network, in terms of implementation nova-network appears to be simpler and quicker solution, but, I guess, it doesn't make huge difference.

About os-vif -- is that the right and the only place to collaborate on it: https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/mitaka-nova-os-vif-lib ?"}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-11-11 12:40:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2

To be clear, nova-network is mostly closed for new features.

Neutron is the future of networking, so new features, like free bsd support, should be added there.

So I have a feeling we need to block this until we know what OS-VIF-Lib is doing. As we have that as a priority for this release, I don't want things like this to distract from that.

Catch me on IRC or via email to discuss this more."}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-11-11 12:40:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

IRC = johnthetubaguy'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-11-24 17:48:55.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

lets take this out of the review queue for now? please restore if you still want this for mitaka.'}, {'account_id': 6509, 'date': '2015-11-24 18:26:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Yeah, it should be dropped for now, at least while the future of os-vif is not clear.'}]

it didn't do anything to handle it. Domains just hung in ERROR.

closes-bug: #1416264
(cherry picked from commit ed2861a0193e2b5ebbb89a8d8fb04fdded976483)

Conflicts:

Change-Id: I4348f714868f38c2549c516fe83cce608c0c8d59

commit_message:
Handle NO_DOMAIN status

Previous to this patch, when MiniDNS got a `NO_DOMAIN` status back,
it didn't do anything to handle it. Domains just hung in ERROR.

closes-bug: #1416264
(cherry picked from commit ed2861a0193e2b5ebbb89a8d8fb04fdded976483)

Conflicts:
	designate/tests/unit/test_central/test_basic.py

Change-Id: I4348f714868f38c2549c516fe83cce608c0c8d59

This is icky. I'm not sure backporting the neutron change is the right solution here. 

liberty released against oslo.messaging <2.6.0. Operator/distros/vendors assumption is that stable/liberty will continue to function with the oslo.messaging they released/deployed/tested with liberty (ie, ubuntu shipped liberty /w oslo.messaging 1.8.3) Backporting the neutron change means stable/liberty needs to raise its oslo.messaging to >2.6.0, causing all those people the headache of having to 1) be aware of this 2) upgrade what should be a static dependency from underneath their stable deployment.

commit_message:
Block oslo.messaging 2.6.0->2.9.0 in Liberty

2.6.0 changed module names for notification drivers in change:

1893c495f6e9ba53c7d93ad99f679f44f66837ef

This broke Neutron's notification system (and maybe other projects).

Paths were updated in Neutron for Mitaka in change:

225663888e71d44e9732951f515da925b8799b74

And a minimum set on oslo.messaging in mitaka g-r.

To fix Neutron in stable/liberty, oslo.messaging now has an alias for
the older messaging driver paths:

15cd99050c6d2714b90059e0faad9f9e3409eaaa

This is released in oslo.messaging 3.0.0. So we need to block all
oslo.messaging releases that don't have the internal driver paths, which
is all releases between 2.6.0 and 2.9.0.

Depends-On: I9f3c2e391f810927c5b9b541213655030a464c24

Co-Authored-By: Matt Riedemann <mriedem@us.ibm.com>

Closes-Bug: #1513630

Change-Id: I5d15366a212c6ed21f33bfe011876fc2bb56997c

commit_message:
don't pass aodh options to oslo.db engine facade

oslo.db EngineFacade class only support options defined by oslo.db,
but we also pass options defined by aodh, so oslo.db complains
with a warning message:

NotSupportedWarning: Configuration option(s) ['alarm_connection', \
'alarm_history_time_to_live'] not supported

This patch makes sure only options defined by oslo.db will be sent
to EngineFacade

Change-Id: I4c259f29af1cab60c3aee41a610b12f64ed5f2d5
Closes-Bug: #1516515

commit_message:
docs: describe migration and other movement concepts

Migration (including cold and live migration), resize and shelve
are three concepts at the API level that support three distinct
sets of use cases. These all involve movement of servers and
so provide opportunity for operational efficiency.

This patch adds a section to the server concepts that outlines
the purpose behind the actions and the operational efficiencies
that can be gained by them.

blueprint complete-todo-in-api-concept-doc

Change-Id: I6b9c6c179c1bdd9400abae7deb1918b370ddaefd

commit_message:
Make acl_scenarios tests' keystonemiddleware cache work flexibly

Token cache keys in keystonemiddleware 2.0 are sha256 hashes of the
token key. This is _not_ the case in keystonemiddleware <2.0. This
change adjusts the FakeMemcache to support both types of key.

Closes-Bug: #1519382
Change-Id: Idcba48b227e8921a67f5af27f723810704ae790b

Add release notes for mitaka thus far

Add release notes for patches that have landed in mitaka prior to
using reno for release notes management.

Change-Id: Icaa875c344e75888764a94aff941f442126403df

I would support a change in documentation that says "keystone is a standard python wsgi service and can be deployed in any wsgi capable environment" or something similar.

I think if we start listing what those environments are we need to be testing them and we need to be maintaining documentation for how you go about setting each of them up and keep that up to date and figure out what parts of keystone are available in each case.

If we just say keystone is wsgi then people are more than welcome to figure out how to deploy it in their own environment, but i think we should only provide documentation for what we know we are able to support for all scenarios keystone supports (SAML and other apache plugins).'}, {'account_id': 1941, 'date': '2015-11-18 04:44:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Top and Bottom Padding should be removed from navbar-brand

When using a theme other than 'default', a custom logo that is too
big won't be sized to fit inside of the header exactly perfectly.
The 'default' theme does this.  The style just needs to be moved
outside of 'default' theme to be global.

Change-Id: I241e49ad94cba24592209f5f4f23eedeb0e592a6
Closes-Bug: #1518123

Currently each Versioned Object needs to implement its own get_by_id,
with this patch they don't need anymore, since it will be included in
the base class CinderObject and it will work for all the objects.

This will help for other things like having a refresh method or
conditional updates in the objects.

commit_message:
Move get_by_id to CinderObject

Currently each Versioned Object needs to implement its own get_by_id,
with this patch they don't need anymore, since it will be included in
the base class CinderObject and it will work for all the objects.

This will help for other things like having a refresh method or
conditional updates in the objects.

Related-Bug: #1490944
Related-Bug: #1238093
Related-Bug: #1490946
Related-Bug: #1469659
Change-Id: I355dc8eaefed93003533ee083f74acd1315f057e

commit_message:
Remove example extension

we will no longer be supporting extensions, everything is in keystone
proper, with varying degrees of stability.

Change-Id: I419df55ebe760cbd36a1c93ff7e712cfd3e8405f
Implements: bp move-extensions
Closes-Bug: #1519244

Thanks for the review and thoughts Thiago.

Byte order is how it currently sorts (its the default sorting in sqllite. This patch is a rather old one, when I first pushed it up, the idea of having an option to sort alphabetically came up, and had been added to the patch.. then people asked thought about sorting by date and size. So this was added too. After a while there was too much in this change (and reverse listing was what we really wanted) so it was split into two patches. Reverse listing and other sorting. The latter was decided not required and was eventually abandoned.

So byte order is all there is now.. date and size are not indexed, that was one of the reasons for abandoning, however arguably because name is alpha could be added.

As for pseudo folders, good catch, I'll take a look :) This was one of my earlier patches and haven't touched it for a while, so need to get my head around it again :)"}, {'account_id': 7233, 'date': '2015-07-22 05:43:03.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 7233, 'date': '2015-07-22 06:20:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

[{'created': '2014-09-11 07:16:51.000000000', 'message': 'Add container reverse listings and basic ordering

This change adds the ability to tell the container server to reverse
the object listings. This is done by sending a reverse=TRUE_VALUE,

Where TRUE_VALUE is one of the values true can be in common/utils:

  TRUE_VALUES = set(('true', '1', 'yes', 'on', 't', 'y'))

For example:

  curl -i -X GET -H "X-Auth-Token: $TOKEN" $STORAGE_URL/c/?reverse=on

Then goes one step further, by default sqlite's ordering is in byte
order rather then alphabetic. This change adds the option to tell the
container server to use alphabetic ordering if required with:

  curl -i -X GET -H "X-Auth-Token: $TOKEN" $STORAGE_URL/c/?order=alpha

The order option of byte (?order=byte) is also available but this is
also the default value so can be ommited.

Taking the following list:

  ['o1', 'O1', 'o10', 'o2', 'O4', 'o3']

Byte order is:

  ['O1', 'O4', 'o1', 'o10', 'o2', 'o3']

Where are alphabetic ordering would be:

  ['O1', 'o1', 'o10', 'o2', 'o3', 'O4']

NOTE: In byte order uppercase letters come before lowercase.

I borrowed the swapping of the markers code from Kevin's old change,
thanks Kevin.

DocImpact
Co-Authored-By: Kevin McDonald <kmcdonald@softlayer.com>
Implements: blueprint reverse-object-listing

Change-Id: I5eb655360ac95042877da26d18707aebc11c02f6

commit_message:
Add container and account reverse listings

This change adds the ability to tell the container or account server to
reverse their listings. This is done by sending a reverse=TRUE_VALUE,

Where TRUE_VALUE is one of the values true can be in common/utils:

  TRUE_VALUES = set(('true', '1', 'yes', 'on', 't', 'y'))

For example:

  curl -i -X GET -H "X-Auth-Token: $TOKEN" $STORAGE_URL/c/?reverse=on

I borrowed the swapping of the markers code from Kevin's old change,
thanks Kevin. And Tim Burke added some real nuggets of awesomeness.

DocImpact
Co-Authored-By: Kevin McDonald <kmcdonald@softlayer.com>
Co-Authored-By: Tim Burke <tim.burke@gmail.com>
Implements: blueprint reverse-object-listing

Change-Id: I5eb655360ac95042877da26d18707aebc11c02f6

commit_message:
Copy the env to the backup stack in failed update

When an update fails, we currently update the environment of the stack
to contain both the new and old parameters and types. Unfortunately we
don't do that for the backup stack which is reused. This patch adds the
environment change.

Change-Id: I4dc5dd35e4aeee498dd8960a1000913e97b924d5
Closes-Bug: 1508096
(cherry picked from commit 88da460316e2c18b3ceb58f51dcf0bda717a18a3
                       and 13c68910704844719b2d3de353d2db276377bf11)

commit_message:
Add Bandit Config Change Spec

This commit adds a spec for a group of changes that will rework
how Bandit deals with config.  The approach will remove unused
options, move profiles to separate purpose-built files, and use
sensible defaults for plugins when possible.

Change-Id: I2a65d799466650a76b41ec6ecd748ef5156f57b7

/run/udev contains the udev information needed for the lvm tools
/run and /dev must be bound in for this to work properly

Change-Id: Icfe07c4ce3673310cc24591b42c107c9710cd3ac
Closes-Bug: #1518454
Closes-Bug: #1487780
Related-Bug: #1487807
'}]
commit_message:
Fix udev cinder issue

/run/udev contains the udev information needed for the lvm tools
/run and /dev must be bound in for this to work properly

Change-Id: Icfe07c4ce3673310cc24591b42c107c9710cd3ac
Closes-Bug: #1518454
Closes-Bug: #1487780
Related-Bug: #1487807

commit_message:
Remove eventlet usage

This removes entirely our usage of eventlet and its ugly monkey-patching
in favor of a threaded approach.

Implements: remove-eventlet
Change-Id: Ib5f623e2d1ff9e9254601ad091bf5b53ab32000d

Did you tox -r before you ran your tests locally, they are failing for me locally. There are six gabbi related failures, primarily because of cascading failures off initial ones. For example the failure on: gabbi.driver.test_gabbi_meters_post_counter_with_good_timestamp.test_request

is because the timestamp is bad:

'{"error_message": {"faultstring": "Invalid input for field/attribute samples. Value: \'[{\'resource_id\': \'aa9431c1-8d69-4ad3-803a-8d4a6b89fdaa\', \'timestamp\': \'2013-01-01 23:23:20\', \'counter_unit\': \'instance\', \'counter_volume\': 3, \'counter_name\': \'apples\', \'counter_type\': \'gauge\'}]\'. \'2013-01-01 23:23:20\' is not a legal datetime value", "faultcode": "Client", "debuginfo": null}}'

which suggests that some bit of time parsing which used to be a bit more lenient isn't being lenient any more.

I would guess it is a question of timing, not your changes, will try on master.'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2015-07-02 11:41:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Works on master. The croniter package appears to be the culprit. It is having some kind of side effect on time parsing.

If you have it in the virtenv and import it in `ceilometer/__init__.py` the tests ought to pass.

Remove alarming code

Since we moved all the alarming code and subsystem to the Aodh project,
remove it from Ceilometer.

commit_message:
Drop root for ironic

Updates to ensure commands run in the ironic containers
are done as the 'ironic' user rather than root.

Change-Id: I491041ce02fb5dd3eb60c6ae9169f26d8a8919dd
Partially-Implements: blueprint drop-root

commit_message:
Flip Neutron's unit tests to -constraints

This flips master and stable/liberty to use -constraints unit tests as
voting.  The unconstrained jobs are dropped from master and liberty.

Implements Blueprint: Requirements-Management

Change-Id: I152ed78813e46ffc3f72ff7dec5ed2872268f5bd

commit_message:
Add T111 hacking rule for consistent DELETE method

As the consistent-service-method-names bp, "DELETE /resources/<id>"
methods' names should be "delete_<resource name>".
So this patch adds it as the hacking rule.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: I36592a91001361d816e302745fe8417aee5e7565

commit_message:
Refactor T110 rule

We need to implement more rules for the other methods(DELETE/POST/PUT)
for consistent method names. Before doing that, this patch separates
common part from T110 rule for sharing it.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: I24c90d331a45a4f6ad50303c4d17e7cd4d2d784c

commit_message:
Use Tempest-lib's compute limits_client

Compute limits_client has been migrated to
tempest-lib- I80c6e148ae30148e591d24675fe068c829a0867a

Now Tempest-lib provides this client as stable interface so Tempest
should start using this from lib and remove its own copy.
Also remove its unit tests.

This commits makes Tempest to use compute limits_client
from Tempest-lib.

Change-Id: I915deafd6e513f98e4d621d4e91409dd35d6e19e

commit_message:
Use Tempest-lib's compute instance_usage_audit_logs

Compute instance_usage_audit_logs has been migrated to
tempest-lib- I3c104b49903e5762041c370e3e9803a382de76fa

Now Tempest-lib provides this client as stable interface so Tempest
should start using this from lib and remove its own copy.
Also remove its unit tests.

This commits makes Tempest to use compute instance_usage_audit_logs
from Tempest-lib.

Change-Id: I2f1e1c0500eb1f52a3fe64031d79f01b9bd57dc2

commit_message:
Set ZUUL_BRANCH using BRANCH if not available

In most cases, ZUUL_BRANCH is set in gate, but not all the time. One
exception is e.g. periodic stable jobs, where there is no actual patch
to validate, hence no ZUUL_REF or ZUUL_BRANCH is set. In that case, we
need to help zuul-cloner to determine the proper branch to fetch
neutron.

It could be achieved by e.g. hardcoding the branch using --zuul_branch
CLI argument passed into zuul-cloner. In this patch, I instead set
ZUUL_BRANCH to BRANCH that seems to be always present in all kinds of
jobs. It is then used by zuul-cloner to choose the correct branch.

This fixes the issue for stable/liberty periodic jobs for neutron-lbaas
when we tried to validate it against neutron/master.

Change-Id: I360239a1443f8d4e16210a1ef743912e1bf85f41

commit_message:
use last specified value for duplicate dimension

When user specifies a dimension for multiple times, monasca_manager
cannot generate dimension url, because it expects a string but gets
a list. For such case, we should use the last specified value.

Change-Id: Ic90447fabf7a00d034ba4c423fea34c30da222e7
Closes-Bug: #1518664

commit_message:
Tweak the way plugin attributes are loaded

By using the setdefault method to add plugin parameters to the kwargs
passed to load_from_options() we are unnecessarily calling the getter
function when the value may not be saved.

This has generally not been a problem however if we start doing things
like prompting users for a password in the getter this is an expensive
and disruptive operation for a parameter that may not be stored.

Change-Id: Ic8dc3a425662c4a89372f178b175b8caab44e024

commit_message:
Change tests to adapt alarm spliting

Currently, alarm module has been diceded to be splitted out from
Ceilometer tree, named as aodh. This change make tests adapt to the
spliting.

NOTE: This change temporarily set the aodh service availability config
option as False, it is mainly because the alarming service spliting
change[1] need to be merged now. I will enable aodh in tempest and
make it works by another change.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/197161/

Closes-Bug: #1509885
Change-Id: I3983128d2d964b0f1f3326948b27f5d94df65a04
